{"title_page": "Maulik Pancholy", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Maulik Pancholy\n| image              = Maulik Pancholy 2019 Texas Book Festival.jpg\n| caption            = Pancholy at the 2019 Texas Book Festival\n| birth_name         = Maulik Navin Pancholy\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1974|1|18}}\n| birth_place        = [[Dayton, Ohio]], U.S.\n| alma_mater         = [[Northwestern University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Yale University]] ([[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]])\n| occupation         = Actor, author\n| years_active       = 1998\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Ryan Corvaia|2014}}\n| website            = maulikpancholy.com\n}}\n'''Maulik Navin Pancholy''' ({{IPAc-en|m|o\u028a|l|i\u02d0|k|_|n|\u0251\u02d0|v|\u026a|n|_|p|\u00e6|n|\u02c8|t\u0283|o\u028a|l|i}}, born January 18, 1974) is an [[Americans|American]] actor and author who is best known for his roles as Jonathan on ''[[30 Rock]]'', [[Baljeet Tjinder]] in ''[[Phineas and Ferb]]'', Neal in the first season of ''[[Whitney (TV series)|Whitney]]'', and characters named Sanjay Patel in both ''[[Weeds (TV series)|Weeds]]'' and ''[[Sanjay and Craig]]''. His debut novel, ''The Best at It'' (from [[Balzer + Bray]]/[[HarperCollins]]), is about a gay, Indian American boy coming into his own.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.harpercollins.com/9780062866417/the-best-at-it|title=The Best at It - Maulik Pancholy - Hardcover|website=HarperCollins Publishers: World-Leading Book Publisher|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-05}}</ref> \n\n==Early life==\nPancholy was born in [[Dayton, Ohio]]. He moved around while growing up, living in Ohio, Indiana, and Texas before his family settled in [[Tampa, Florida]], where he attended junior high and high school at Berkeley Preparatory School.<ref>{{cite news|title=Angry Reader of the Week: Maulik Pancholy|url=http://blog.angryasianman.com/2014/10/angry-reader-of-week-maulik-pancholy.html|accessdate=April 24, 2018|work=Angry Asian Man|date=October 10, 2014}}</ref> His family comes from [[Gujarat]], and his grandparents lived in [[Ahmedabad]].<ref name=\"abcdlady\">{{cite news|last1=Dayal|first1=Priyanka|title=Rock Star: A Conversation with Maulik Pancholy|url=http://www.abcdlady.com/2009-05/art1.php|accessdate=29 April 2015|work=ABCD Lady}}</ref> He is a 1991 graduate of the [[Berkeley Preparatory School]] in Tampa, and went on to major in Theatre at [[Northwestern University]], where he received his [[bachelor's degree]] in 1995.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0997689/bio |title=Maulik Pancholy - Biography |work=The Internet Movie Database | accessdate=15 March 2012 }}</ref> He then attended the [[Yale School of Drama]], where he received his [[Master of Fine Arts]] in 2003.<ref name=greg>{{cite news | author=Gregory Kirschling | date=11 May 2007 | title=Maulik Pancholy: You Might Know Me From...The 33-year-old | work=Entertainment Weekly | url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20037736,00.html | accessdate=15 March 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Maulik pancholy cropped.jpg|thumb|190px|Pancholy in 2007]]\nPancholy played the character of [[Jonathan (30 Rock)|Jonathan]] on the award-winning NBC series ''[[30 Rock]],'' Sanjay on Showtime's [[Weeds (TV series)|''Weeds'']], Neal on the first season of NBC's [[Whitney (TV series)|''Whitney'']], and voiced the characters of [[Baljeet Tjinder]] on Disney's [[Phineas and Ferb|''Phineas & Ferb'']] and Sanjay on Nickelodeon's [[Sanjay and Craig|''Sanjay & Craig'']].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0997689/|title=Maulik Pancholy|website=IMDb|access-date=2019-09-05}}</ref> Additional television work includes guest roles on ''[[The Good Fight]]'', ''[[The Good Wife]]'', [[Elementary (TV series)|''Elementary'']], [[Dynasty (2017 TV series)|''Dynasty'']], ''[[Friends from College]]'', ''[[Tracey Takes On...]]'', ''[[The Sopranos]]'', ''[[Law & Order: Criminal Intent]]'', and ''[[The Comeback (TV series)|The Comeback]]''.<ref name=greg/>\n\nOn February 13, 2017 StarTrek.com stated that Pancholy will play Nambue, Chief Medical Officer of the USS ''Shenzhou'' in the upcoming TV series ''[[Star Trek: Discovery]]''. His character appeared in the pilot episode, \"[[The Vulcan Hello]]\", which aired on 24th September 2017, and streamed on CBS's online service in America and [[Netflix]] abroad.<ref>Schwindt, Oriana (February 13, 2017). \"'Star Trek: Discovery' Adds Three More Starfleet Members\". Variety. Archived from the original on February 14, 2017. Retrieved February 14, 2017</ref>\n\nHis stage credits in New York City include the Culture Project's production of ''Guantanamo: Honor Bound to Defend Freedom'' in 2004, a workshop of the play ''Morbidity & Mortality'' at the historic [[Cherry Lane Theatre]] in 2005, and the lead role in ''India Awaiting'' at the Samuel Beckett Theatre. In January 2015, he joined the cast of [[Terrence McNally]]'s ''[[It's Only a Play]]'', replacing [[Rupert Grint]] when the production's Broadway run was extended.<ref>Gordon, David.[http://www.theatermania.com/new-york-city-theater/news/martin-short-katie-finneran-maulik-pancholy-photos_71297.html \"It's Only a Play's New Stars Martin Short, Katie Finneran, and Maulik Pancholy Meet the Press\"] theatermania.com, January 13, 2015</ref> Washington DC stage credits include Katherina in an all male version of the Shakespeare Theatre Company's \"The Taming of The Shrew\" in 2016. He starred as 'Kevin' in the world premiere engagement of Ken Urban's ''The Remains'' at the Studio Theatre in 2018. \n\nIn 2019, Pancholy played 'Tommy' in Bess Wohl's ''Grand Horizons'' at the [[Williamstown Theatre Festival]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Williamstown-Theatre-Festival-Announces-Additional-Casting-Ellen-Barkin-Thomas-Sadoski-and-More-20190412|title=Williamstown Theatre Festival Announces Additional Casting; Ellen Barkin, Thomas Sadoski, and More|last=Desk|first=BWW News|website=BroadwayWorld.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-05}}</ref> It was announced that he will reprise the role in [[Second Stage Theater|Second Stage]]'s Broadway production of the play at the [[Hayes Theater|Helen Hayes Theater]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/michael-urie-thomas-sadoski-broadway-grand-horizons-maulik-pancholy-ashley-park-1202661414/|title=Michael Urie, Thomas Sadoski, Maulik Pancholy Among Cast Of Broadway-Bound \u2018Grand Horizons\u2019|last=Evans|first=Greg|last2=Evans|first2=Greg|date=2019-08-05|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2019-09-05}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPancholy [[Coming out|came out]] as [[gay]] in a November 2013 interview with ''[[Out (magazine)|Out]]'' in which he discussed his partner of nine years, chef and caterer Ryan Corvaia.<ref>{{cite news | date=11 November 2013 | title=Out100: Maulik Pancholy | work=Out Magazine | url=http://www.out.com/out-exclusives/out100-2013/2013/11/11/out100-maulik-pancholy | accessdate=11 November 2013}}</ref> They were engaged at the [[Taj Mahal]] in January 2014 and were married in September that year.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kennedy|first1=Ed|title=Maulik Pancholy Woke Up a Married Man|url=http://www.thebacklot.com/maulik-pancholy-woke-up-a-married-man/09/2014/|accessdate=29 April 2015|work=The Backlot|date=September 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\nPancholy speaks [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] and [[Spanish language|Spanish]]. He is also proficient in [[Hindi]], which he speaks in the ''30 Rock'' episode \"[[Khonani]]\".<ref name=\"abcdlady\"/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Pancholy|first1=Maulik|title=That Khonani brings it out of me|url=https://twitter.com/maulikpancholy/status/99328868263018496|date=4 August 2011|publisher=Twitter|accessdate=29 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Political activism===\nOn April 25, 2014, Pancholy was named to [[President of the United States|President]] [[Barack Obama]]'s Advisory Commission on Asian Americans and Pacific Islanders as part of the [[White House Initiative on Asian Americans and Pacific Islanders]].<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.advocate.com/politics/2014/04/27/out-actor-maulik-pancholy-named-white-house-commission |title=Out Actor Maulik Pancholy Named to White House Commission |last=Garcia |first=Michelle |date=27 April 2014 |magazine=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]] |accessdate=22 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=gaystar>{{cite web |url=https://www.gaystarnews.com/article/out-actor-maulik-pancholy-appointed-white-house-advisory-commission280414/ |title=Out actor Maulik Pancholy appointed to White House advisory commission |last=Withers |first=James |date=27 April 2014 |publisher=[[Gay Star News]] |accessdate=22 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=whitehouse>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=President Obama Announces his Intent to Appoint Fourteen Individuals to the President\u2019s Advisory Commission on Asian Americans and Pacific Islanders |url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/the-press-office/2014/04/24/president-obama-announces-his-intent-appoint-fourteen-individuals-presid |publisher=The White House |date=24 April 2014 |access-date=22 June 2017}}</ref> On February 25, 2017, Pancholy and nine other members of the commission resigned from their positions, citing administrative actions by President [[Donald Trump]] that they claimed went \"against the commission's principles\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/asian-america/10-resign-president-s-advisory-commission-asian-americans-pacific-islanders-n721386 |title=10 Resign from President\u2019s Advisory Commission on Asian Americans and Pacific Islanders |last=Lee |first=Traci G. |date=16 February 2017 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |accessdate=22 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.avclub.com/article/30-rocks-maulik-pancholy-just-quit-presidential-co-250606 |title=''30 Rock''\u2019s Maulik Pancholy just quit a presidential commission because of Donald Trump |last=Hughes |first=William |date=18 February 2017 |website=[[The A.V. Club]] |publisher=[[The Onion|Onion, Inc.]] |accessdate=22 June 2017}}</ref> \n\nPancholy is active with several non-profit and social policy organizations including [[Asian Americans Advancing Justice - Los Angeles]], the New York City Anti-Violence Project, and [[OutRight Action International]], formerly known as the International Gay and Lesbian Human Rights Commission.<ref name=whitehouse /><ref name=gaystar />\n\nPancholy is the Chair and Co-Founder of the anti-bullying nonprofit Act To Change. He helped launch the campaign during his time serving on President Obama's Advisory Commission. Act To Change was transitioned outside of the White House after the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://acttochange.org/background/|title=Act to Change {{!}}|date=2018-12-05|website=Act to Change|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-05}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#b0c4de; text-align:center;\"\n! Year\n! Film\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1999 || ''Pok\u00e9mon Trading Card Game: Trainer Video'' || Adult Card Trader || \n|-\n| 2005 || ''[[Hitch (film)|Hitch]]'' || Raoul || \n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| 2006 || ''[[Friends with Money]]'' || Flirtatious Waiter || \n|-\n|''Quarter Life Crisis'' || Neil Desai ||\n|-\n|[[Park (2007 film)|''Park'']]|| Babar || \n|-\n| 2008 ||''[[27 Dresses]]'' || Trent ||\n|- \n| 2009 || ''[[Love N' Dancing]]'' || Gunmay ||\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"| 2010  || ''[[Love Ranch]]'' || Samir Singh || \n|-\n|''Good Sharma'' || Samir ||\n|-\n|''[[Tug (film)|Tug]]'' || Carl ||\n|-\n|''[[See You in September (film)|See You in September]]'' || Roger ||\n|-\n|''[[Raspberry Magic]]'' || Amrish Patil ||\n|-\n| 2011 || ''[[Horrible Bosses]]''<ref>{{cite web|author=Sabrina Siddiqui |url=http://divanee.com/2010/11/11/30-rock-weeds-star-maulik-pancholy-on-his-myriad-roles/ |title=30 Rock & Weeds Star on Alec Baldwin, Tina Fey and Shattering Stereotypes | work=Divanee |date=11 November 2010 |accessdate=15 March 2012}}</ref> || Gregory || Voice only\n|-\n|2011\n|[[Phineas and Ferb the Movie: Across the 2nd Dimension|''Phineas and Ferb the Movie: Across the 2nd Dimension'']]\n|Baljeet Tjinder\n|Voice only\n|-\n| 2012 || ''[[Treasure Buddies]]'' || Babi || Voice only\n|-\n| 2013 || ''[[Super Buddies (film)|Super Buddies]]'' || Curly the Pig || Voice only \n|-\n|2020\n|''[[Phineas and Ferb the Movie: Candace Against the Universe]]''\n|Baljeet Tjinder\n|Voice only\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#b0c4de; text-align:center;\"\n! Year !! Show !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"| 1998 || ''[[USA High]]'' || Achmed || Episode: \"Jackson Moves Out\"\n|-\n| ''[[City Guys]]'' || Rasheed || Episode: \"Jamal Got His Gun\"\n|-\n| ''[[Malibu, CA (TV series)|Malibu, CA]]'' || Haji || Episode: \"Surf Sale\"\n|-\n| ''[[Felicity (TV series)|Felicity]]'' || T.A. || Episode: \"Finally\"\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| 1999 || ''[[Tracey Takes On...]]'' || Roberto || Episode: \"Road Rage\"\n|-\n| ''[[Jack & Jill (TV series)|Jack & Jill]]'' || Barto's Classmate || \n|-\n| ''[[Charmed]]'' || Treasure Hunter #1 ||\n|-\n| 2000 || ''[[Family Law (TV series)|Family Law]]'' || Clerk || Episode: \"Metamorphosis\"\n|-\n| 2005\u20132009, 2012 ||''[[Weeds (TV series)|Weeds]]'' || Sanjay Patel  || Recurring seasons 1\u20135; 8\n|-\n| 2005 || ''[[The Comeback (TV series)|The Comeback]]'' || Kaveen Kahan || 3 episodes\n|-\n| 2006\u201311, 2012 || ''[[30 Rock]]'' || [[Jonathan (30 Rock)|Jonathan]] || Recurring seasons 1\u20132; Main seasons 3\u20135; 7\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2007 || ''[[Law & Order: Criminal Intent]]'' || Aziz Gabriel/Dani Hasni || Episode: \"Stress Position\" <br> \"World's Fair\"\n|-\n| ''[[The Sopranos]]'' || Dr. Ajit Gupte || Episode: \"[[Stage 5 (The Sopranos)|Stage 5]]\"\n|-\n| 2007\u20132015 ||''[[Phineas and Ferb]]'' || [[List of Phineas and Ferb characters#Baljeet Tjinder|Baljeet Tjinder]] || rowspan=\"2\"| Voice only\n|-\n| 2009 || ''[[The Replacements (TV series)|The Replacements]]'' || Kamil Sattar (voice)\n|-\n| 2010 || ''[[Running Wilde]]'' || Himself || Episode: \"Mental Flaws\"\n|-\n| 2011 || ''[[Web Therapy (TV series)|Web Therapy]]'' || Kamal Prakash || Recurring; season 1\n|-\n| 2011\u20132012 ||''[[Whitney (TV series)|Whitney]]'' || Neal || Main (season 1)\n|-\n| 2013\u20132016 ||''[[Sanjay and Craig]]'' || Sanjay Patel || Main role, voice only<br>60 episodes\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2014 || ''[[The Good Wife]]'' || Dev Jain || Episode \"Parallel Construction, Bitches\"\n|-\n| ''[[Wander Over Yonder]]'' || N/ ||\n|-\n| 2016 || ''[[The Muppets (TV series)|The Muppets]]'' || Photographer || Episode: \"Got Silk?\"\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2017 || ''[[Star Trek Discovery]]'' || Dr. Nambue || \n|-\n| ''[[Friends from College]]'' || Patel || Episode: \"A Night of Surprises\"\n|-\n| 2017, 2019 || ''[[Milo Murphy's Law]]'' || Neal<br>Baljeet Tjinder || Episodes: \"Love Toboggan\" <br>\u00b0\"The Phineas and Ferb Effect\"\n|-\n| 2018 || ''[[Elementary (TV series)|Elementary]]'' || Alfonse Kapoor || Episode: \"Our Time Is Up\"\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"| 2019 || ''[[Dynasty (2017 TV series)|Dynasty]]'' || Kenneth Desai || Episode: \"[[Filthy Games]]\"\n|-\n| ''[[American Dad!]]'' || Nudist (voice) || Episode: \"Stan & Francine & Connie & Ted\"\n|-\n| ''[[The Good Fight]]'' || Dev Jain || Episode: \"The One Where Diane Joins the Resistance\" <br> \"The One Where Kurt Saves Diane\"\n|-\n| ''[[Mickey Mouse Mixed-Up Adventures]]'' || Jasper (voice) || Episode: \"Here, Kitty, Kitty, Kitty!\"\n|}\n\n===Stage===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Location\n! Category\n|-\n| 2003\n|''[[Aunt Dan and Lemon]]''\n| Marty\n| [[Acorn Theatre]]\n| Off-Broadway\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''Guantanamo: Honor Bound to Defend Freedom''\n| Ruhel Ahmed\n|[[Lynn Redgrave Theater]]\n| Off-Broadway\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''Morbidity & Mortality''\n| {{n/a}}\n| [[Cherry Lane Theatre]]\n| Off-Broadway \n|-\n| 2014\u20132015\n| ''[[It's Only a Play]]''\n| Frank Finger\n| [[Gerald Schoenfeld Theatre]] and [[Bernard B. Jacobs Theatre]]\n| Broadway\n|-\n| 2016\n|''[[The Taming of the Shrew]]''\n| Katharina Minola\n| [[Shakespeare Theatre Company]] at [[Sidney Harman Hall]]\n| Regional\n|-\n| 2018\n|''[[Good for Otto]]''\n| Alex\n| [[Pershing Square Signature Center]]\n| Off-Broadway\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''The Remains''\n| Kevin\n| [[Studio Theatre (Washington, D.C.)|Studio Theatre]]\n| Regional\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''Grand Horizons''\n| Tommy\n| [[Hayes Theater]]\n| Broadway\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[http://niralimagazine.com/2006/12/out-of-the-weeds/ Out of the Weeds, Nirali Magazine, December 2006]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070929102701/http://televisionwithoutpity.com/portal/site/TelevisionWithoutPity/menuitem.766266d5c663f366b180b41045001d30/?vgnextoid=774fbbd6e4144110VgnVCM1000006dc1d240RCRD&vgnextfmt=default&ShowName=Weeds Television Without Pity- The Maulik Pancholy Interview]\n*{{IMDb name|997689|Maulik Pancholy}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Film|LGBT}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pancholy, Maulik}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male actors of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from the United States]]\n[[Category:Gay actors]]\n[[Category:Northwestern University School of Communication alumni]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Dayton, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Yale School of Drama alumni]]\n[[Category:American people of Gujarati descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT American people of Asian descent]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Ohio]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Maulik Pancholy\n| image              = Maulik Pancholy 2019 Texas Book Festival.jpg\n| caption            = Pancholy at the 2019 Texas Book Festival\n| birth_name         = Maulik Navin Pancholy\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1974|1|18}}\n| birth_place        = [[Dayton, Ohio]], U.S.\n| alma_mater         = [[Northwestern University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Yale University]] ([[Master of Fine Arts|MFA]])\n| occupation         = Actor, author\n| years_active       = 1998\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|Ryan Corvaia|2014}}\n| website            = maulikpancholy.com\n}}\n'''Maulik Navin Pancholy''' ({{IPAc-en|m|o\u028a|l|i\u02d0|k|_|n|\u0251\u02d0|v|\u026a|n|_|p|\u00e6|n|\u02c8|t\u0283|o\u028a|l|i}}, born January 18, 1974) is an [[Americans|American]] actor and author who is best known for his roles as Jonathan on ''[[30 Rock]]'', [[Baljeet Tjinder]] in ''[[Phineas and Ferb]]'', Neal in the first season of ''[[Whitney (TV series)|Whitney]]'', and characters named Sanjay Patel in both ''[[Weeds (TV series)|Weeds]]'' and ''[[Sanjay and Craig]]''. His debut novel, ''The Best at It'' (from [[Balzer + Bray]]/[[HarperCollins]]), is about a gay, Indian American boy coming into his own.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.harpercollins.com/9780062866417/the-best-at-it|title=The Best at It - Maulik Pancholy - Hardcover|website=HarperCollins Publishers: World-Leading Book Publisher|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-05}}</ref> \n\n==Early life==\nPancholy was born in [[Dayton, Ohio]]. He moved around while growing up, living in Ohio, Indiana, and Texas before his family settled in [[Tampa, Florida]], where he attended junior high and high school at Berkeley Preparatory School.<ref>{{cite news|title=Angry Reader of the Week: Maulik Pancholy|url=http://blog.angryasianman.com/2014/10/angry-reader-of-week-maulik-pancholy.html|accessdate=April 24, 2018|work=Angry Asian Man|date=October 10, 2014}}</ref> His family comes from [[Gujarat]], and his grandparents lived in [[Ahmedabad]].<ref name=\"abcdlady\">{{cite news|last1=Dayal|first1=Priyanka|title=Rock Star: A Conversation with Maulik Pancholy|url=http://www.abcdlady.com/2009-05/art1.php|accessdate=29 April 2015|work=ABCD Lady}}</ref> He is a 1991 graduate of the [[Berkeley Preparatory School]] in Tampa, and went on to major in Theatre at [[Northwestern University]], where he received his [[bachelor's degree]] in 1995.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0997689/bio |title=Maulik Pancholy - Biography |work=The Internet Movie Database | accessdate=15 March 2012 }}</ref> He then attended the [[Yale School of Drama]], where he received his [[Master of Fine Arts]] in 2003.<ref name=greg>{{cite news | author=Gregory Kirschling | date=11 May 2007 | title=Maulik Pancholy: You Might Know Me From...The 33-year-old | work=Entertainment Weekly | url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20037736,00.html | accessdate=15 March 2012 }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Maulik pancholy cropped.jpg|thumb|190px|Pancholy in 2007]]\nPancholy played the character of [[Jonathan (30 Rock)|Jonathan]] on the award-winning NBC series ''[[30 Rock]],'' Sanjay on Showtime's [[Weeds (TV series)|''Weeds'']], Neal on the first season of NBC's [[Whitney (TV series)|''Whitney'']], and voiced the characters of [[Baljeet Tjinder]] on Disney's [[Phineas and Ferb|''Phineas & Ferb'']] and Sanjay on Nickelodeon's [[Sanjay and Craig|''Sanjay & Craig'']]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/name/nm0997689/|title=Maulik Pancholy|website=IMDb|access-date=2019-09-05}}</ref>. Additional television work includes guest roles on ''[[The Good Fight]]'', ''[[The Good Wife]]'', [[Elementary (TV series)|''Elementary'']], [[Dynasty (2017 TV series)|''Dynasty'']], ''[[Friends from College]]'', ''[[Tracey Takes On...]]'', ''[[The Sopranos]]'', ''[[Law & Order: Criminal Intent]]'', and ''[[The Comeback (TV series)|The Comeback]]''.<ref name=greg/>\n\nOn February 13, 2017 StarTrek.com stated that Pancholy will play Nambue, Chief Medical Officer of the USS ''Shenzhou'' in the upcoming TV series ''[[Star Trek: Discovery]]''. His character appeared in the pilot episode, \"[[The Vulcan Hello]]\", which aired on 24th September 2017, and streamed on CBS's online service in America and [[Netflix]] abroad.<ref>Schwindt, Oriana (February 13, 2017). \"'Star Trek: Discovery' Adds Three More Starfleet Members\". Variety. Archived from the original on February 14, 2017. Retrieved February 14, 2017</ref>\n\nHis stage credits in New York City include the Culture Project's production of ''Guantanamo: Honor Bound to Defend Freedom'' in 2004, a workshop of the play ''Morbidity & Mortality'' at the historic [[Cherry Lane Theatre]] in 2005, and the lead role in ''India Awaiting'' at the Samuel Beckett Theatre. In January 2015, he joined the cast of [[Terrence McNally]]'s ''[[It's Only a Play]]'', replacing [[Rupert Grint]] when the production's Broadway run was extended.<ref>Gordon, David.[http://www.theatermania.com/new-york-city-theater/news/martin-short-katie-finneran-maulik-pancholy-photos_71297.html \"It's Only a Play's New Stars Martin Short, Katie Finneran, and Maulik Pancholy Meet the Press\"] theatermania.com, January 13, 2015</ref> Washington DC stage credits include Katherina in an all male version of the Shakespeare Theatre Company's \"The Taming of The Shrew\" in 2016. He starred as 'Kevin' in the world premiere engagement of Ken Urban's ''The Remains'' at the Studio Theatre in 2018. \n\nIn 2019, Pancholy played 'Tommy' in Bess Wohl's ''Grand Horizons'' at the [[Williamstown Theatre Festival]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/article/Williamstown-Theatre-Festival-Announces-Additional-Casting-Ellen-Barkin-Thomas-Sadoski-and-More-20190412|title=Williamstown Theatre Festival Announces Additional Casting; Ellen Barkin, Thomas Sadoski, and More|last=Desk|first=BWW News|website=BroadwayWorld.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-05}}</ref>. It was announced that he will reprise the role in [[Second Stage Theater|Second Stage]]'s Broadway production of the play at the [[Hayes Theater|Helen Hayes Theater]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2019/08/michael-urie-thomas-sadoski-broadway-grand-horizons-maulik-pancholy-ashley-park-1202661414/|title=Michael Urie, Thomas Sadoski, Maulik Pancholy Among Cast Of Broadway-Bound \u2018Grand Horizons\u2019|last=Evans|first=Greg|last2=Evans|first2=Greg|date=2019-08-05|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2019-09-05}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPancholy [[Coming out|came out]] as [[gay]] in a November 2013 interview with ''[[Out (magazine)|Out]]'' in which he discussed his partner of nine years, chef and caterer Ryan Corvaia.<ref>{{cite news | date=11 November 2013 | title=Out100: Maulik Pancholy | work=Out Magazine | url=http://www.out.com/out-exclusives/out100-2013/2013/11/11/out100-maulik-pancholy | accessdate=11 November 2013}}</ref> They were engaged at the [[Taj Mahal]] in January 2014 and were married in September that year.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kennedy|first1=Ed|title=Maulik Pancholy Woke Up a Married Man|url=http://www.thebacklot.com/maulik-pancholy-woke-up-a-married-man/09/2014/|accessdate=29 April 2015|work=The Backlot|date=September 28, 2014}}</ref>\n\nPancholy speaks [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] and [[Spanish language|Spanish]]. He is also proficient in [[Hindi]], which he speaks in the ''30 Rock'' episode \"[[Khonani]]\".<ref name=\"abcdlady\"/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Pancholy|first1=Maulik|title=That Khonani brings it out of me|url=https://twitter.com/maulikpancholy/status/99328868263018496|date=4 August 2011|publisher=Twitter|accessdate=29 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Political activism===\nOn April 25, 2014, Pancholy was named to [[President of the United States|President]] [[Barack Obama]]'s Advisory Commission on Asian Americans and Pacific Islanders as part of the [[White House Initiative on Asian Americans and Pacific Islanders]].<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.advocate.com/politics/2014/04/27/out-actor-maulik-pancholy-named-white-house-commission |title=Out Actor Maulik Pancholy Named to White House Commission |last=Garcia |first=Michelle |date=27 April 2014 |magazine=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]] |accessdate=22 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=gaystar>{{cite web |url=https://www.gaystarnews.com/article/out-actor-maulik-pancholy-appointed-white-house-advisory-commission280414/ |title=Out actor Maulik Pancholy appointed to White House advisory commission |last=Withers |first=James |date=27 April 2014 |publisher=[[Gay Star News]] |accessdate=22 June 2017}}</ref><ref name=whitehouse>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=President Obama Announces his Intent to Appoint Fourteen Individuals to the President\u2019s Advisory Commission on Asian Americans and Pacific Islanders |url=https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/the-press-office/2014/04/24/president-obama-announces-his-intent-appoint-fourteen-individuals-presid |publisher=The White House |date=24 April 2014 |access-date=22 June 2017}}</ref> On February 25, 2017, Pancholy and nine other members of the commission resigned from their positions, citing administrative actions by President [[Donald Trump]] that they claimed went \"against the commission's principles\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/asian-america/10-resign-president-s-advisory-commission-asian-americans-pacific-islanders-n721386 |title=10 Resign from President\u2019s Advisory Commission on Asian Americans and Pacific Islanders |last=Lee |first=Traci G. |date=16 February 2017 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |accessdate=22 June 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.avclub.com/article/30-rocks-maulik-pancholy-just-quit-presidential-co-250606 |title=''30 Rock''\u2019s Maulik Pancholy just quit a presidential commission because of Donald Trump |last=Hughes |first=William |date=18 February 2017 |website=[[The A.V. Club]] |publisher=[[The Onion|Onion, Inc.]] |accessdate=22 June 2017}}</ref> \n\nPancholy is active with several non-profit and social policy organizations including [[Asian Americans Advancing Justice - Los Angeles]], the New York City Anti-Violence Project, and [[OutRight Action International]], formerly known as the International Gay and Lesbian Human Rights Commission.<ref name=whitehouse /><ref name=gaystar />\n\nPancholy is the Chair and Co-Founder of the anti-bullying nonprofit Act To Change. He helped launch the campaign during his time serving on President Obama's Advisory Commission. Act To Change was transitioned outside of the White House after the [[2016 United States presidential election|2016 presidential election]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://acttochange.org/background/|title=Act to Change {{!}}|date=2018-12-05|website=Act to Change|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-05}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#b0c4de; text-align:center;\"\n! Year\n! Film\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1999 || ''Pok\u00e9mon Trading Card Game: Trainer Video'' || Adult Card Trader || \n|-\n| 2005 || ''[[Hitch (film)|Hitch]]'' || Raoul || \n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| 2006 || ''[[Friends with Money]]'' || Flirtatious Waiter || \n|-\n|''Quarter Life Crisis'' || Neil Desai ||\n|-\n|[[Park (2007 film)|''Park'']]|| Babar || \n|-\n| 2008 ||''[[27 Dresses]]'' || Trent ||\n|- \n| 2009 || ''[[Love N' Dancing]]'' || Gunmay ||\n|-\n|rowspan=\"5\"| 2010  || ''[[Love Ranch]]'' || Samir Singh || \n|-\n|''Good Sharma'' || Samir ||\n|-\n|''[[Tug (film)|Tug]]'' || Carl ||\n|-\n|''[[See You in September (film)|See You in September]]'' || Roger ||\n|-\n|''[[Raspberry Magic]]'' || Amrish Patil ||\n|-\n| 2011 || ''[[Horrible Bosses]]''<ref>{{cite web|author=Sabrina Siddiqui |url=http://divanee.com/2010/11/11/30-rock-weeds-star-maulik-pancholy-on-his-myriad-roles/ |title=30 Rock & Weeds Star on Alec Baldwin, Tina Fey and Shattering Stereotypes | work=Divanee |date=11 November 2010 |accessdate=15 March 2012}}</ref> || Gregory || Voice only\n|-\n|2011\n|[[Phineas and Ferb the Movie: Across the 2nd Dimension|''Phineas and Ferb the Movie: Across the 2nd Dimension'']]\n|Baljeet Tjinder\n|Voice only\n|-\n| 2012 || ''[[Treasure Buddies]]'' || Babi || Voice only\n|-\n| 2013 || ''[[Super Buddies (film)|Super Buddies]]'' || Curly the Pig || Voice only \n|-\n|2020\n|''[[Phineas and Ferb the Movie: Candace Against the Universe]]''\n|Baljeet Tjinder\n|Voice only\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-  style=\"background:#b0c4de; text-align:center;\"\n! Year !! Show !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"| 1998 || ''[[USA High]]'' || Achmed || Episode: \"Jackson Moves Out\"\n|-\n| ''[[City Guys]]'' || Rasheed || Episode: \"Jamal Got His Gun\"\n|-\n| ''[[Malibu, CA (TV series)|Malibu, CA]]'' || Haji || Episode: \"Surf Sale\"\n|-\n| ''[[Felicity (TV series)|Felicity]]'' || T.A. || Episode: \"Finally\"\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| 1999 || ''[[Tracey Takes On...]]'' || Roberto || Episode: \"Road Rage\"\n|-\n| ''[[Jack & Jill (TV series)|Jack & Jill]]'' || Barto's Classmate || \n|-\n| ''[[Charmed]]'' || Treasure Hunter #1 ||\n|-\n| 2000 || ''[[Family Law (TV series)|Family Law]]'' || Clerk || Episode: \"Metamorphosis\"\n|-\n| 2005\u20132009, 2012 ||''[[Weeds (TV series)|Weeds]]'' || Sanjay Patel  || Recurring seasons 1\u20135; 8\n|-\n| 2005 || ''[[The Comeback (TV series)|The Comeback]]'' || Kaveen Kahan || 3 episodes\n|-\n| 2006\u201311, 2012 || ''[[30 Rock]]'' || [[Jonathan (30 Rock)|Jonathan]] || Recurring seasons 1\u20132; Main seasons 3\u20135; 7\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2007 || ''[[Law & Order: Criminal Intent]]'' || Aziz Gabriel/Dani Hasni || Episode: \"Stress Position\" <br> \"World's Fair\"\n|-\n| ''[[The Sopranos]]'' || Dr. Ajit Gupte || Episode: \"[[Stage 5 (The Sopranos)|Stage 5]]\"\n|-\n| 2007\u20132015 ||''[[Phineas and Ferb]]'' || [[List of Phineas and Ferb characters#Baljeet Tjinder|Baljeet Tjinder]] || rowspan=\"2\"| Voice only\n|-\n| 2009 || ''[[The Replacements (TV series)|The Replacements]]'' || Kamil Sattar (voice)\n|-\n| 2010 || ''[[Running Wilde]]'' || Himself || Episode: \"Mental Flaws\"\n|-\n| 2011 || ''[[Web Therapy (TV series)|Web Therapy]]'' || Kamal Prakash || Recurring; season 1\n|-\n| 2011\u20132012 ||''[[Whitney (TV series)|Whitney]]'' || Neal || Main (season 1)\n|-\n| 2013\u20132016 ||''[[Sanjay and Craig]]'' || Sanjay Patel || Main role, voice only<br>60 episodes\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2014 || ''[[The Good Wife]]'' || Dev Jain || Episode \"Parallel Construction, Bitches\"\n|-\n| ''[[Wander Over Yonder]]'' || N/ ||\n|-\n| 2016 || ''[[The Muppets (TV series)|The Muppets]]'' || Photographer || Episode: \"Got Silk?\"\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| 2017 || ''[[Star Trek Discovery]]'' || Dr. Nambue || \n|-\n| ''[[Friends from College]]'' || Patel || Episode: \"A Night of Surprises\"\n|-\n| 2017, 2019 || ''[[Milo Murphy's Law]]'' || Neal<br>Baljeet Tjinder || Episodes: \"Love Toboggan\" <br>\u00b0\"The Phineas and Ferb Effect\"\n|-\n| 2018 || ''[[Elementary (TV series)|Elementary]]'' || Alfonse Kapoor || Episode: \"Our Time Is Up\"\n|-\n|rowspan=\"4\"| 2019 || ''[[Dynasty (2017 TV series)|Dynasty]]'' || Kenneth Desai || Episode: \"[[Filthy Games]]\"\n|-\n| ''[[American Dad!]]'' || Nudist (voice) || Episode: \"Stan & Francine & Connie & Ted\"\n|-\n| ''[[The Good Fight]]'' || Dev Jain || Episode: \"The One Where Diane Joins the Resistance\" <br> \"The One Where Kurt Saves Diane\"\n|-\n| ''[[Mickey Mouse Mixed-Up Adventures]]'' || Jasper (voice) || Episode: \"Here, Kitty, Kitty, Kitty!\"\n|}\n\n===Stage===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Location\n! Category\n|-\n| 2003\n|''[[Aunt Dan and Lemon]]''\n| Marty\n| [[Acorn Theatre]]\n| Off-Broadway\n|-\n| 2004\n| ''Guantanamo: Honor Bound to Defend Freedom''\n| Ruhel Ahmed\n|[[Lynn Redgrave Theater]]\n| Off-Broadway\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''Morbidity & Mortality''\n| {{n/a}}\n| [[Cherry Lane Theatre]]\n| Off-Broadway \n|-\n| 2014\u20132015\n| ''[[It's Only a Play]]''\n| Frank Finger\n| [[Gerald Schoenfeld Theatre]] and [[Bernard B. Jacobs Theatre]]\n| Broadway\n|-\n| 2016\n|''[[The Taming of the Shrew]]''\n| Katharina Minola\n| [[Shakespeare Theatre Company]] at [[Sidney Harman Hall]]\n| Regional\n|-\n| 2018\n|''[[Good for Otto]]''\n| Alex\n| [[Pershing Square Signature Center]]\n| Off-Broadway\n|-\n| 2018\n| ''The Remains''\n| Kevin\n| [[Studio Theatre (Washington, D.C.)|Studio Theatre]]\n| Regional\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''Grand Horizons''\n| Tommy\n| [[Hayes Theater]]\n| Broadway\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*[http://niralimagazine.com/2006/12/out-of-the-weeds/ Out of the Weeds, Nirali Magazine, December 2006]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070929102701/http://televisionwithoutpity.com/portal/site/TelevisionWithoutPity/menuitem.766266d5c663f366b180b41045001d30/?vgnextoid=774fbbd6e4144110VgnVCM1000006dc1d240RCRD&vgnextfmt=default&ShowName=Weeds Television Without Pity- The Maulik Pancholy Interview]\n*{{IMDb name|997689|Maulik Pancholy}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Film|LGBT}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pancholy, Maulik}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male actors of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from the United States]]\n[[Category:Gay actors]]\n[[Category:Northwestern University School of Communication alumni]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Dayton, Ohio]]\n[[Category:Yale School of Drama alumni]]\n[[Category:American people of Gujarati descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Indian descent]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT American people of Asian descent]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Ohio]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maulik_Pancholy"}
{"title_page": "Maud Menten", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian physician and chemist}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Maud Leonora Menten\n| birth_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image = Maud Leonora Menten (1879-1960).jpg\n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1879|3|20|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = Port Lambton, Ontario\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1960|7|17|1879|3|20}}\n| death_place = Leamington, Ontario, Canada\n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- \n                      {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} -->\n| other_names = \n| residence = \n| citizenship = \n| nationality = Canadian\n| fields = \n| workplaces = {{Plainlist|\n* [[University of Toronto]], Canada\n* [[Rockefeller Institute for Medical Research]], US\n* [[New York Infirmary for Women and Children]], US\n* [[University of Berlin]], Germany She also went to the University Of Pittsburgh \n\n* [[University of Chicago]], US\n* [[University of Pittsburgh]], US\n* [[British Columbia Medical Research Institute]], Canada}}\n| patrons = \n| alma_mater = [[University of Toronto]]\n| thesis_title = The Alkalinity of the Blood in Malignancy and Other Pathological Conditions; Together with Observations on the Relation of the Alkalinity of the Blood to Barometric Pressure\n| thesis_url = \n| thesis_year = 1916\n| doctoral_advisor = \n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students = \n| known_for = Michaelis-Menten equation, contributions to enzyme kinetics and histochemistry\n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| influences = \n| influenced = \n| awards = \n| signature = \n| signature_alt = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n| spouse = \n| child = \n}}\n\n'''Maud Leonora Menten''' (March 20, 1879 &ndash; July 17, 1960) was a [[Canadians|Canadian]] bio-medical and medical researcher who made significant contributions to [[enzyme kinetics]] and [[histochemistry]]. She is primarily known for her work with [[Leonor Michaelis]] on enzyme kinetics and co-authored [[Michaelis\u2013Menten kinetics|Michaelis\u2013Menten equation]] in 1913. \n\nMaud Menten was born in [[Port Lambton, Ontario]] and studied medicine at the [[University of Toronto]] (B.A. 1904, M.B. 1907, M.D. 1911, Ph.D., 1916). She was among the first women in Canada to earn a medical doctorate.<ref name=\"Can Med Hall Fame\" /> She completed her thesis work at [[University of Chicago]]. At that time women were not allowed to do research in Canada, so she decided to do research in other countries such as the United States and Germany.\n\nIn 1912 she moved to [[Berlin]] where she worked with [[Leonor Michaelis]] and co-authored their paper in ''Biochemische Zeitschrift''<ref name=\"Michaelis-Menten equation paper\" /> which showed that the rate of an enzyme-catalyzed reaction is proportional to the amount of the enzyme-substrate complex. This relationship between reaction rate and enzyme\u2013substrate concentration is known as the [[Michaelis\u2013Menten equation]]. \n\nAfter studying with Michaelis in Germany she entered graduate school at the [[University of Chicago]] where she obtained her PhD in 1916.<ref name=\"Profile\">{{cite web |title=Leonor Michaelis and Maud Menten |url=https://www.sciencehistory.org/historical-profile/leonor-michaelis-and-maud-leonora-menten |website=[[Science History Institute]]|accessdate=20 March 2018}}</ref> Her dissertation was titled \"The Alkalinity of the Blood in Malignancy and Other Pathological Conditions; Together with Observations on the Relation of the Alkalinity of the Blood to Barometric Pressure\". Menten worked  at the [[University of Pittsburgh]] (1923&ndash;1950),<ref>{{Cite journal \n| last1 = Menten | first1 = M. \n| title = A Study of the Oxidase Reaction with alpha-Naphthol and Paraphenylenediamine \n| journal = The Journal of Medical Research \n| volume = 40 \n| issue = 3 \n| pages = 433\u2013458.3 \n| year = 1919 \n| pmid = 19972493 \n| pmc = 2104435\n}}</ref> becoming Assistant Professor and then Associate Professor in the [[University of Pittsburgh School of Medicine|School of Medicine]] and head of pathology at the [[UPMC Children's Hospital of Pittsburgh|Children's Hospital of Pittsburgh]]. Her final promotion to full Professor, in 1948, was at the age of 69 in the last year of her career.<ref name=\"Profile\" /><ref name=\"Miss Menten\">{{cite web|last1=Skloot|first1=Rebecca|title=Some called her Miss Menten|url=http://pittmed.health.pitt.edu/oct_2000/miss_menten.pdf|publisher=University of Pittsburgh School of Medicine magazine|accessdate=14 October 2014|date=Oct 2000}}</ref> Her final academic post was as a research fellow at the British Columbia Medical Research Institute.\n\n==Early life and work==\n\nThe Menten family moved to Harrison Mills, where Maud's mother worked as a postmistress. After completing secondary school, Menten attended the University of Toronto where she earned a bachelor of arts degree in 1904 and a master's degree in physiology in 1907. While earning her graduate degree, she worked as a demonstrator in the university's physiology lab.\n\nAs Menten wanted to further her medical research, she found that opportunities in Canada were scarce for women at the time. As a result she accepted a fellowship at the Rockefeller Institute for Medical Research and left for in New York City in 1907; there she studied the effect of radium bromide on cancerous tumors in rats.<ref name=\"Miss Menten\" /> Menten and two other scientists published the results of their experiment, producing the Rockefeller Institute's first monograph.<ref name=\"Miss Menten\" /><ref name=Monograph>{{cite book|last1=Jobling|first1=J W|last2=Flexner|first2=Simon|last3=Menten|first3=Maud L|title=Tumors of animals|date=1910|publisher=[[Rockefeller Institute for Medical Research]]}}</ref>  Menten worked as an intern at the New York Infirmary for Women and Children. After a year at the Institute, Menten returned to Canada and began her studies at the University of Toronto where in 1911 she became one of the first Canadian women to qualify as a medical doctor.<ref name=\"Miss Menten\" />\n\n== The Michaelis-Menten Equation ==\nIn 1912, Menten came back to medical research, working with renowned surgeon [[George Washington Crile|George Crile]] on the control of acid-base balance during anaesthesia. Around this time she became acquainted with Leonor Michaelis, he was known then as one of the world-leading experts in pH and buffers.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.rsc.org/diversity/175-faces/all-faces/professor-maud-l-menten/|title=Maud Menten was a biochemical and medical researcher who co-devised one of the fundamental models in enzyme kinetics.|last=Winship|first=Douglas|date=May 2015|website=Royal Society of Chemistry}}</ref> Menten became attracted to Michaelis' early work in [[enzyme kinetics]], despite his modest laboratory establishment in Berlin, and made the difficult decision to cross the sea to work with Michaelis. Menten's early years in Germany was met with financial and social hardships, she took a paid position at a Berlin hospital to cover her living and travel expense as well as beginning to learn German when she first came to Berlin.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nFrom 1905 to 1921, Michaelis and Menten succeeded in expressing mathematically the relationship they were investigating, which demonstrated that each enzyme not only has its own substrate but also that at sufficient concentrations of substrate it has its own rate of causing that substrate to change chemically. One of the constants used in expressing this rate is now called the Michaelis-Menten constant.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencehistory.org/historical-profile/leonor-michaelis-and-maud-leonora-menten|title=Leonor Michaelis and Maud Leonora Menten|date=December 12, 2017}}</ref>The [[Michaelis\u2013Menten kinetics|Michaelis\u2013Menten]] equations, is considered her most famous work  with Michaelis,<ref name=\"Michaelis-Menten equation paper\" /> based on earlier findings of Victor Henri.\n\n== Other work ==\nAfter her research in Berlin, Menten enrolled in University of Chicago, where in 1916 she obtained a PhD in biochemistry. In 1923, Menten still could not find an academic position for women in Canada; she took a position as part of the faculty of the medical school at the University of Pittsburgh while serving as a clinical pathologist at Children\u2019s Hospital in Pittsburgh. Despite the demands both jobs had, Menten found time to maintained an active research program, authoring or coauthoring more than 70 publications. Although her promotion from assistant to associate professor was timely, she was not made a full professor until she was 70 years old, within one year of retirement.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nMenten also invented the azo-dye coupling reaction for [[alkaline phosphatase]], which is still used in histochemistry. She characterised bacterial toxins from ''B. paratyphosus'', ''Streptococcus scarlatina'' and ''[[Salmonella]] ssp.'' that were used in a successful immunisation program against scarlet fever in Pittsburgh in the 1930s - 1940s.<ref name=\"PittsburghPressNoScareletFever\">{{cite news|title=Scarlet fever deaths avoided in city|date=May 19, 1942|publisher=The Pittsburgh Press}}</ref>  She also conducted the first [[electrophoresis|electrophoretic]] separation of blood haemoglobin proteins in 1944. She worked on the properties of [[hemoglobin]], regulation of [[blood sugar]] level, and kidney function.<ref name=\"Nature obit\" /> \n\nAfter her retirement from the University of Pittsburgh in 1950, she returned to Canada where she continued to do cancer research at the British Columbia Medical Research Institute (1951&ndash;1953). \n\nPoor health forced Menten's retirement in 1955, and she died July 17, 1960, at the age of 81, in [[Leamington, Ontario]].<ref name=\"Miss Menten\" /><ref name=\"Can Med Hall Fame\" />\n\n==Personal life==\n\n[[Rebecca Skloot]] portrays Menten as a petite dynamo of a woman who wore \"Paris hats, blue dresses with stained-glass hues, and Buster Brown shoes.\"<ref name=\"Miss Menten\" /> She drove a Model T Ford through the University of Pittsburgh area for some 32 years and enjoyed many adventurous and artistic hobbies. She played the clarinet, painted paintings worthy of art exhibitions,<ref name=\"Can Med Hall Fame\" /> climbed mountains, went on an Arctic expedition, and enjoyed astronomy. By the time of her death, she mastered several languages, including Russian, French, German, Italian, and at least one Native-American language, [[Halkomelem]].<ref name=\"Miss Menten\" /><ref>{{cite journal|authorlink1=Athel Cornish-Bowden|last1=Cornish-Bowden |first1=Athel |last2=Lagnado |first2=John |title=Maud Leonora Menten: A woman at the dawn of biochemistry |journal=The Biochemist |date=December 2013 |page=46-47 |url=http://bip.cnrs-mrs.fr/bip10/CB-Lagnado-13.pdf |accessdate=10 April 2019}}</ref>\nAlthough Menten did most of her research in the United States, she retained her Canadian citizenship throughout her life.\n\n==Honors==\n\nThroughout her career Menten was affiliated with many scientific societies.\n\nAt Menten's death, colleagues Aaron H. Stock and Anna-Mary Carpenter honored the Canadian biochemist in an obituary in Nature: \"Menten was untiring in her efforts on behalf of sick children. She was an inspiring teacher who stimulated medical students, resident physicians and research associates to their best efforts. She will long be remembered by her associates for her keen mind, for a certain dignity of manner, for unobtrusive modesty, for her wit, and above all for her enthusiasm for research.\" <ref name=\"Nature obit\">{{cite journal|last1=Stock|first1=Aaron|last2=Carpenter|first2=Anna-Mary|title=Prof. Maud Menten|journal=Nature|date=1961|volume=189|issue=4769|page=965|doi=10.1038/189965a0|bibcode=1961Natur.189..965S}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998 she was posthumously inducted into the Canadian Medical Hall of Fame.<ref name=\"Can Med Hall Fame\">{{cite web|title=Dr. Maud Menten|url=http://www.cdnmedhall.org/inductees/dr-maud-l-menten|publisher=The Canadian Medical Hall of Fame|accessdate=14 October 2014|df=}}</ref> She was also honored at the University of Toronto with a plaque and at the University of Pittsburgh with memorial lectures and a named chair.<ref name=\"Miss Menten\" /> Port Lambton, Canada, where Menten was born, installed a commemorative bronze plaque about her in 2015.<ref name=PortLambtonplaque>{{cite news|last1=Hnatyshyn|first1=Carl|title=Plaques for historical figures approved for St. Clair Twp|url=http://www.wallaceburgcourierpress.com/2014/10/09/plaques-for-historical-figures-approved-for-st-clair-twp|accessdate=2 June 2015|agency=Postmedia Network|publisher=Wallaceburg Courier Press|date=9 Oct 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\n\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Menten | first1 = ML. | last2 = Willms | first2 = M. | last3 = Wright | first3 = WD. | year = 1953 | title = Nucleic acid content of splenic lymphocytes in normal and leukemic mice | url = | journal = Cancer Research | volume = 13 | issue = | pages = 729\u2013732 }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Neale | first1 = AE. | last2 = Menten | first2 = ML. | year = 1948 | title = Tumors of the thymus in children | url = | journal = American Journal of Diseases of Children | volume = 76 | issue = | pages = 102\u2013108 | doi=10.1001/archpedi.1948.02030030109012}}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Menten | first1 = ML. | last2 = Fetterman | first2 = GH. | year = 1948 | title = Coronary sclerosis in infancy - report of 3 autopsied cases, 2 in siblings | url = | journal = American Journal of Clinical Pathology | volume = 18 | issue = 10| pages = 805\u2013810 | doi=10.1093/ajcp/18.10.805}}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Menten | first1 = ML. | last2 = Janouch | first2 = M. | year = 1946 | title = Changes in alkaline phosphatase of kidney following renal damage with alloxan | url = | journal = Proceedings of the Society for Experimental Biology and Medicine | volume = 63 | issue = | pages = 33\u201337 | doi=10.3181/00379727-63-15482}}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Troll | first1 = MM. | last2 = Menten | first2 = ML. | year = 1945 | title = Salicylate poisoning - report of 4 cases | url = | journal = American Journal of Diseases of Children | volume = 69 | issue = | pages = 37\u201343 | doi=10.1001/archpedi.1945.02020130044006}}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Menten | first1 = ML. | last2 = Junge | first2 = J. | last3 = Green | first3 = MH. | year = 1944 | title = Distribution of alkaline phosphatase in kidney following the use of histochemical azo dye test | url = | journal = Proceedings of the Society for Experimental Biology and Medicine | volume = 57 | issue = | pages = 82\u201386 | doi=10.3181/00379727-57-14706}}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Menten | first1 = ML. | last2 = Junge | first2 = J. | last3 = Green | first3 = MH. | year = 1944 | title = A coupling histochemical azo dye test for alkaline phosphatase in the kidney | url = | journal = Journal of Biological Chemistry | volume = 153 | issue = | pages = 471\u2013477 }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Andersch | first1 = MA | last2 = Wilson | first2 = DA | last3 = Menten | first3 = ML. | year = 1944 | title = Sedimentation constants and electrophoretic mobilities of adult and fetal carbonylhemoglobin | url = | journal = Journal of Biological Chemistry | volume = 153 | issue = | pages = 301\u2013305 }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = King | first1 = CG. | last2 = Menten | first2 = ML. | year = 1935 | title = The influence of vitamin C level upon resistance to diphtheria toxin I. Changes in body weight and duration of life | url = | journal = Journal of Nutrition | volume = 10 | issue = | pages = 129\u2013140 }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Menten | first1 = ML | year = 1927 | title = Changes in the blood sugar of the cod, sculpin, and pollock during asphyxia | url = | journal = Journal of Biological Chemistry | volume = 72 | issue = | pages = 249\u2013253 }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Menten | first1 = ML | year = 1922 | title = Pathological lesions produced in the kidney by small doses of mercuric chloride | url = | journal = Journal of Medical Research | volume = 43 | issue = | pages = 315\u2013321 }}\n* Menten, ML., \"A study of the oxidase reaction with a-naphthol and paraphenylenediamine.\" ''Journal of Medical Research'', Vol 40 (1919) pp.&nbsp;433 - U22\n* Michaelis L., Menten, ML. \"The kinetics of invertin action\" ''Biochemische Zeitschrift'', Vol 49 (1913) pp.&nbsp;335\u2013369 (Translation by T.R.C. Boyde in ''FEBS Letters'', vol 587 (2013) pp.&nbsp;2712\u20132720)<ref name=\"Michaelis-Menten equation paper\">{{cite journal|last1=Michaelis|first1=Leonor|title=Die Kinetik der Invertinwirkung|journal=Biochemische Zeitschrift|date=4 Feb 1913|volume=49|issue=17|pages=335\u2013369|doi=10.1016/j.febslet.2013.07.015|pmid=23867202|trans-title=The kinetics of invertin action}}</ref>\n* Jobling, J. W., Flexner, S., Menten, M. L. ''Tumors of animals'' New York: Rockefeller Institute for Medical Research, 1910\n\n==See also==\n*[[Timeline of women in science]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://pittmed.health.pitt.edu/oct_2000/miss_menten.pdf Some called her Miss Menten] by Rebecca Skloot in Pittmed (University of Pittsburgh School of Medicine magazine), October 2000\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Johnson | first1 = Kenneth A. | last2 = Goody | first2 = Roger S. | date = October 2011 | title = The Original Michaelis Constant: Translation of the 1913 Michaelis-Menten Paper | journal = Biochemistry | volume = 50 | issue = 39| pages = 8264\u20138269 | pmc=3381512 | pmid=21888353 | doi=10.1021/bi201284u}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Canadian Medical Hall of Fame}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Menten, Maud}}\n[[Category:1879 births]]\n[[Category:1960 deaths]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriate academics in the United States]]\n[[Category:Canadian women scientists]]\n[[Category:Canadian medical researchers]]\n[[Category:People from Lambton County]]\n[[Category:University of Pittsburgh faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Toronto alumni]]\n[[Category:Canadian women chemists]]\n[[Category:Canadian chemists]]\n[[Category:20th-century women scientists]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Ontario]]\n[[Category:Physicians from Ontario]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian physicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian scientists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian physician and chemist}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name = Maud Leonora Menten\n| birth_name = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image = Maud Leonora Menten (1879-1960).jpg\n| image_size = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1879|3|20|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = Port Lambton, Ontario\n| death_date = {{death date and age|1960|7|17|1879|3|20}}\n| death_place = Leamington, Ontario, Canada\n| resting_place = \n| resting_place_coordinates = <!-- \n                      {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} -->\n| other_names = \n| residence = \n| citizenship = \n| nationality = Canadian\n| fields = \n| workplaces = {{Plainlist|\n* [[University of Toronto]], Canada\n* [[Rockefeller Institute for Medical Research]], US\n* [[New York Infirmary for Women and Children]], US\n* [[University of Berlin]], Germany She also went to the University Of Pittsburgh \n\n* [[University of Chicago]], US\n* [[University of Pittsburgh]], US\n* [[British Columbia Medical Research Institute]], Canada}}\n| patrons = \n| alma_mater = [[University of Toronto]]\n| thesis_title = The Alkalinity of the Blood in Malignancy and Other Pathological Conditions; Together with Observations on the Relation of the Alkalinity of the Blood to Barometric Pressure\n| thesis_url = \n| thesis_year = 1916\n| doctoral_advisor = \n| academic_advisors = \n| doctoral_students = \n| notable_students = \n| known_for = Michaelis-Menten equation, contributions to enzyme kinetics and histochemistry\n| author_abbrev_bot = \n| author_abbrev_zoo = \n| influences = \n| influenced = \n| awards = \n| signature = \n| signature_alt = \n| website = \n| footnotes = \n| spouse = \n| child = \n}}\n\n'''Maud Leonora Menten''' (March 20, 1879 &ndash; July 17, 1960) was a [[Canadians|Canadian]] bio-medical and medical researcher who made significant contributions to [[enzyme kinetics]] and [[histochemistry]]. She is primarily known for her work with [[Leonor Michaelis]] on enzyme kinetics and co-authored [[Michaelis\u2013Menten kinetics|Michaelis\u2013Menten equation]] in 1913. \n\nMaud Menten was born in [[Port Lambton, Ontario]] and studied medicine at the [[University of Toronto]] (B.A. 1904, M.B. 1907, M.D. 1911, Ph.D., 1916). She was among the first women in Canada to earn a medical doctorate.<ref name=\"Can Med Hall Fame\" /> She completed her thesis work at [[University of Chicago]]. At that time women were not allowed to do research in Canada, so she decided to do research in other countries such as the United States and Germany.\n\nIn 1912 she moved to [[Berlin]] where she worked with [[Leonor Michaelis]] and co-authored their paper in ''Biochemische Zeitschrift''<ref name=\"Michaelis-Menten equation paper\" /> which showed that the rate of an enzyme-catalyzed reaction is proportional to the amount of the enzyme-substrate complex. This relationship between reaction rate and enzyme\u2013substrate concentration is known as the [[Michaelis\u2013Menten equation]]. \n\nAfter studying with Michaelis in Germany she entered graduate school at the [[University of Chicago]] where she obtained her PhD in 1916.<ref name=\"Profile\">{{cite web |title=Leonor Michaelis and Maud Menten |url=https://www.sciencehistory.org/historical-profile/leonor-michaelis-and-maud-leonora-menten |website=[[Science History Institute]]|accessdate=20 March 2018}}</ref> Her dissertation was titled \"The Alkalinity of the Blood in Malignancy and Other Pathological Conditions; Together with Observations on the Relation of the Alkalinity of the Blood to Barometric Pressure\". Menten worked  at the [[University of Pittsburgh]] (1923&ndash;1950),<ref>{{Cite journal \n| last1 = Menten | first1 = M. \n| title = A Study of the Oxidase Reaction with alpha-Naphthol and Paraphenylenediamine \n| journal = The Journal of Medical Research \n| volume = 40 \n| issue = 3 \n| pages = 433\u2013458.3 \n| year = 1919 \n| pmid = 19972493 \n| pmc = 2104435\n}}</ref> becoming Assistant Professor and then Associate Professor in the [[University of Pittsburgh School of Medicine|School of Medicine]] and head of pathology at the [[UPMC Children's Hospital of Pittsburgh|Children's Hospital of Pittsburgh]]. Her final promotion to full Professor, in 1948, was at the age of 69 in the last year of her career.<ref name=\"Profile\" /><ref name=\"Miss Menten\">{{cite web|last1=Skloot|first1=Rebecca|title=Some called her Miss Menten|url=http://pittmed.health.pitt.edu/oct_2000/miss_menten.pdf|publisher=University of Pittsburgh School of Medicine magazine|accessdate=14 October 2014|date=Oct 2000}}</ref> Her final academic post was as a research fellow at the British Columbia Medical Research Institute.\n\n==Early life and work==\n\nThe Menten family moved to Harrison Mills, where Maud's mother worked as a postmistress. After completing secondary school, Menten attended the University of Toronto where she earned a bachelor of arts degree in 1904 and a master's degree in physiology in 1907. While earning her graduate degree, she worked as a demonstrator in the university's physiology lab.\n\nAs Menten wanted to further her medical research, she found that opportunities in Canada were scarce for women at the time. As a result she accepted a fellowship at the Rockefeller Institute for Medical Research and left for in New York City in 1907; there she studied the effect of radium bromide on cancerous tumors in rats.<ref name=\"Miss Menten\" /> Menten and two other scientists published the results of their experiment, producing the Rockefeller Institute's first monograph.<ref name=\"Miss Menten\" /><ref name=Monograph>{{cite book|last1=Jobling|first1=J W|last2=Flexner|first2=Simon|last3=Menten|first3=Maud L|title=Tumors of animals|date=1910|publisher=[[Rockefeller Institute for Medical Research]]}}</ref>  Menten worked as an intern at the New York Infirmary for Women and Children. After a year at the Institute, Menten returned to Canada and began her studies at the University of Toronto where in 1911 she became one of the first Canadian women to qualify as a medical doctor.<ref name=\"Miss Menten\" />\n\n== The Michaelis-Menten Equation ==\nIn 1912, Menten came back to medical research, working with renowned surgeon [[George Washington Crile|George Crile]] on the control of acid-base balance during anaesthesia. Around this time she became acquainted with Leonor Michaelis, he was known then as one of the world-leading experts in pH and buffers<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.rsc.org/diversity/175-faces/all-faces/professor-maud-l-menten/|title=Maud Menten was a biochemical and medical researcher who co-devised one of the fundamental models in enzyme kinetics.|last=Winship|first=Douglas|date=May 2015|website=Royal Society of Chemistry}}</ref>. Menten became attracted to Michaelis' early work in [[enzyme kinetics]], despite his modest laboratory establishment in Berlin, and made the difficult decision to cross the sea to work with Michaelis. Menten's early years in Germany was met with financial and social hardships, she took a paid position at a Berlin hospital to cover her living and travel expense as well as beginning to learn German when she first came to Berlin.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nFrom 1905 to 1921, Michaelis and Menten succeeded in expressing mathematically the relationship they were investigating, which demonstrated that each enzyme not only has its own substrate but also that at sufficient concentrations of substrate it has its own rate of causing that substrate to change chemically. One of the constants used in expressing this rate is now called the Michaelis-Menten constant.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencehistory.org/historical-profile/leonor-michaelis-and-maud-leonora-menten|title=Leonor Michaelis and Maud Leonora Menten|date=December 12, 2017}}</ref>The [[Michaelis\u2013Menten kinetics|Michaelis\u2013Menten]] equations, is considered her most famous work  with Michaelis,<ref name=\"Michaelis-Menten equation paper\" /> based on earlier findings of Victor Henri.\n\n== Other work ==\nAfter her research in Berlin, Menten enrolled in University of Chicago, where in 1916 she obtained a PhD in biochemistry. In 1923, Menten still could not find an academic position for women in Canada; she took a position as part of the faculty of the medical school at the University of Pittsburgh while serving as a clinical pathologist at Children\u2019s Hospital in Pittsburgh. Despite the demands both jobs had, Menten found time to maintained an active research program, authoring or coauthoring more than 70 publications. Although her promotion from assistant to associate professor was timely, she was not made a full professor until she was 70 years old, within one year of retirement.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nMenten also invented the azo-dye coupling reaction for [[alkaline phosphatase]], which is still used in histochemistry. She characterised bacterial toxins from ''B. paratyphosus'', ''Streptococcus scarlatina'' and ''[[Salmonella]] ssp.'' that were used in a successful immunisation program against scarlet fever in Pittsburgh in the 1930s - 1940s.<ref name=\"PittsburghPressNoScareletFever\">{{cite news|title=Scarlet fever deaths avoided in city|date=May 19, 1942|publisher=The Pittsburgh Press}}</ref>  She also conducted the first [[electrophoresis|electrophoretic]] separation of blood haemoglobin proteins in 1944. She worked on the properties of [[hemoglobin]], regulation of [[blood sugar]] level, and kidney function.<ref name=\"Nature obit\" /> \n\nAfter her retirement from the University of Pittsburgh in 1950, she returned to Canada where she continued to do cancer research at the British Columbia Medical Research Institute (1951&ndash;1953). \n\nPoor health forced Menten's retirement in 1955, and she died July 17, 1960, at the age of 81, in [[Leamington, Ontario]].<ref name=\"Miss Menten\" /><ref name=\"Can Med Hall Fame\" />\n\n==Personal life==\n\n[[Rebecca Skloot]] portrays Menten as a petite dynamo of a woman who wore \"Paris hats, blue dresses with stained-glass hues, and Buster Brown shoes.\"<ref name=\"Miss Menten\" /> She drove a Model T Ford through the University of Pittsburgh area for some 32 years and enjoyed many adventurous and artistic hobbies. She played the clarinet, painted paintings worthy of art exhibitions,<ref name=\"Can Med Hall Fame\" /> climbed mountains, went on an Arctic expedition, and enjoyed astronomy. By the time of her death, she mastered several languages, including Russian, French, German, Italian, and at least one Native-American language, [[Halkomelem]].<ref name=\"Miss Menten\" /><ref>{{cite journal|authorlink1=Athel Cornish-Bowden|last1=Cornish-Bowden |first1=Athel |last2=Lagnado |first2=John |title=Maud Leonora Menten: A woman at the dawn of biochemistry |journal=The Biochemist |date=December 2013 |page=46-47 |url=http://bip.cnrs-mrs.fr/bip10/CB-Lagnado-13.pdf |accessdate=10 April 2019}}</ref>\nAlthough Menten did most of her research in the United States, she retained her Canadian citizenship throughout her life.\n\n==Honors==\n\nThroughout her career Menten was affiliated with many scientific societies.\n\nAt Menten's death, colleagues Aaron H. Stock and Anna-Mary Carpenter honored the Canadian biochemist in an obituary in Nature: \"Menten was untiring in her efforts on behalf of sick children. She was an inspiring teacher who stimulated medical students, resident physicians and research associates to their best efforts. She will long be remembered by her associates for her keen mind, for a certain dignity of manner, for unobtrusive modesty, for her wit, and above all for her enthusiasm for research.\" <ref name=\"Nature obit\">{{cite journal|last1=Stock|first1=Aaron|last2=Carpenter|first2=Anna-Mary|title=Prof. Maud Menten|journal=Nature|date=1961|volume=189|issue=4769|page=965|doi=10.1038/189965a0|bibcode=1961Natur.189..965S}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998 she was posthumously inducted into the Canadian Medical Hall of Fame.<ref name=\"Can Med Hall Fame\">{{cite web|title=Dr. Maud Menten|url=http://www.cdnmedhall.org/inductees/dr-maud-l-menten|publisher=The Canadian Medical Hall of Fame|accessdate=14 October 2014|df=}}</ref> She was also honored at the University of Toronto with a plaque and at the University of Pittsburgh with memorial lectures and a named chair.<ref name=\"Miss Menten\" /> Port Lambton, Canada, where Menten was born, installed a commemorative bronze plaque about her in 2015.<ref name=PortLambtonplaque>{{cite news|last1=Hnatyshyn|first1=Carl|title=Plaques for historical figures approved for St. Clair Twp|url=http://www.wallaceburgcourierpress.com/2014/10/09/plaques-for-historical-figures-approved-for-st-clair-twp|accessdate=2 June 2015|agency=Postmedia Network|publisher=Wallaceburg Courier Press|date=9 Oct 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\n\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Menten | first1 = ML. | last2 = Willms | first2 = M. | last3 = Wright | first3 = WD. | year = 1953 | title = Nucleic acid content of splenic lymphocytes in normal and leukemic mice | url = | journal = Cancer Research | volume = 13 | issue = | pages = 729\u2013732 }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Neale | first1 = AE. | last2 = Menten | first2 = ML. | year = 1948 | title = Tumors of the thymus in children | url = | journal = American Journal of Diseases of Children | volume = 76 | issue = | pages = 102\u2013108 | doi=10.1001/archpedi.1948.02030030109012}}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Menten | first1 = ML. | last2 = Fetterman | first2 = GH. | year = 1948 | title = Coronary sclerosis in infancy - report of 3 autopsied cases, 2 in siblings | url = | journal = American Journal of Clinical Pathology | volume = 18 | issue = 10| pages = 805\u2013810 | doi=10.1093/ajcp/18.10.805}}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Menten | first1 = ML. | last2 = Janouch | first2 = M. | year = 1946 | title = Changes in alkaline phosphatase of kidney following renal damage with alloxan | url = | journal = Proceedings of the Society for Experimental Biology and Medicine | volume = 63 | issue = | pages = 33\u201337 | doi=10.3181/00379727-63-15482}}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Troll | first1 = MM. | last2 = Menten | first2 = ML. | year = 1945 | title = Salicylate poisoning - report of 4 cases | url = | journal = American Journal of Diseases of Children | volume = 69 | issue = | pages = 37\u201343 | doi=10.1001/archpedi.1945.02020130044006}}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Menten | first1 = ML. | last2 = Junge | first2 = J. | last3 = Green | first3 = MH. | year = 1944 | title = Distribution of alkaline phosphatase in kidney following the use of histochemical azo dye test | url = | journal = Proceedings of the Society for Experimental Biology and Medicine | volume = 57 | issue = | pages = 82\u201386 | doi=10.3181/00379727-57-14706}}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Menten | first1 = ML. | last2 = Junge | first2 = J. | last3 = Green | first3 = MH. | year = 1944 | title = A coupling histochemical azo dye test for alkaline phosphatase in the kidney | url = | journal = Journal of Biological Chemistry | volume = 153 | issue = | pages = 471\u2013477 }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Andersch | first1 = MA | last2 = Wilson | first2 = DA | last3 = Menten | first3 = ML. | year = 1944 | title = Sedimentation constants and electrophoretic mobilities of adult and fetal carbonylhemoglobin | url = | journal = Journal of Biological Chemistry | volume = 153 | issue = | pages = 301\u2013305 }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = King | first1 = CG. | last2 = Menten | first2 = ML. | year = 1935 | title = The influence of vitamin C level upon resistance to diphtheria toxin I. Changes in body weight and duration of life | url = | journal = Journal of Nutrition | volume = 10 | issue = | pages = 129\u2013140 }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Menten | first1 = ML | year = 1927 | title = Changes in the blood sugar of the cod, sculpin, and pollock during asphyxia | url = | journal = Journal of Biological Chemistry | volume = 72 | issue = | pages = 249\u2013253 }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Menten | first1 = ML | year = 1922 | title = Pathological lesions produced in the kidney by small doses of mercuric chloride | url = | journal = Journal of Medical Research | volume = 43 | issue = | pages = 315\u2013321 }}\n* Menten, ML., \"A study of the oxidase reaction with a-naphthol and paraphenylenediamine.\" ''Journal of Medical Research'', Vol 40 (1919) pp.&nbsp;433 - U22\n* Michaelis L., Menten, ML. \"The kinetics of invertin action\" ''Biochemische Zeitschrift'', Vol 49 (1913) pp.&nbsp;335\u2013369 (Translation by T.R.C. Boyde in ''FEBS Letters'', vol 587 (2013) pp.&nbsp;2712\u20132720)<ref name=\"Michaelis-Menten equation paper\">{{cite journal|last1=Michaelis|first1=Leonor|title=Die Kinetik der Invertinwirkung|journal=Biochemische Zeitschrift|date=4 Feb 1913|volume=49|issue=17|pages=335\u2013369|doi=10.1016/j.febslet.2013.07.015|pmid=23867202|trans-title=The kinetics of invertin action}}</ref>\n* Jobling, J. W., Flexner, S., Menten, M. L. ''Tumors of animals'' New York: Rockefeller Institute for Medical Research, 1910\n\n==See also==\n*[[Timeline of women in science]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://pittmed.health.pitt.edu/oct_2000/miss_menten.pdf Some called her Miss Menten] by Rebecca Skloot in Pittmed (University of Pittsburgh School of Medicine magazine), October 2000\n*{{cite journal | last1 = Johnson | first1 = Kenneth A. | last2 = Goody | first2 = Roger S. | date = October 2011 | title = The Original Michaelis Constant: Translation of the 1913 Michaelis-Menten Paper | journal = Biochemistry | volume = 50 | issue = 39| pages = 8264\u20138269 | pmc=3381512 | pmid=21888353 | doi=10.1021/bi201284u}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Canadian Medical Hall of Fame}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Menten, Maud}}\n[[Category:1879 births]]\n[[Category:1960 deaths]]\n[[Category:Canadian expatriate academics in the United States]]\n[[Category:Canadian women scientists]]\n[[Category:Canadian medical researchers]]\n[[Category:People from Lambton County]]\n[[Category:University of Pittsburgh faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Toronto alumni]]\n[[Category:Canadian women chemists]]\n[[Category:Canadian chemists]]\n[[Category:20th-century women scientists]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Ontario]]\n[[Category:Physicians from Ontario]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian physicians]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian scientists]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maud_Menten"}
{"title_page": "Matthew H. Carpenter", "text_new": "{{Infobox Officeholder\n|name          = Matthew Hale Carpenter\n|image         = Matthew H. Carpenter - Brady-Handy.jpg\n|office        = [[President pro tempore of the United States Senate]]\n|term_start    = March 12, 1873\n|term_end      = January 4, 1875\n|predecessor   = [[Henry B. Anthony]]\n|successor     = [[Henry B. Anthony]]\n|jr/sr1         = United States Senator\n|state1         = [[Wisconsin]]\n|term_start1   = March 4, 1879\n|term_end1     = February 24, 1881\n|predecessor1  = [[Timothy O. Howe]]\n|successor1    = [[Angus Cameron (American politician)|Angus Cameron]]\n|term_start2   = March 4, 1869\n|term_end2     = March 3, 1875\n|predecessor2  = [[James Rood Doolittle|James R. Doolittle]]\n|successor2    = [[Angus Cameron (American politician)|Angus Cameron]]\n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1824|12|22}}\n|birth_place   = [[Moretown, Vermont]]\n|death_date    = {{death date and age|1881|2|24|1824|12|22}}\n|death_place   = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n|resting_place = [[Forest Home Cemetery]], [[Milwaukee, Wisconsin]]\n|party         = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|alma_mater    = [[United States Military Academy]] (attended)\n|education     = Studied law with [[Paul Dillingham]] and [[Rufus Choate]]\n|profession    = Attorney\n|spouse        = Caroline Dillingham Carpenter (m. 1855)\n|children      = 2\n|relations     = [[Paul Dillingham]] (father in law)<br/>[[William P. Dillingham]] (brother in law)\n}}\n'''Matthew Hale Carpenter''' (born Decatur Merritt Hammond Carpenter; December 22, 1824 \u2013 February 24, 1881) was an American attorney and U.S. Senator representing the state of [[Wisconsin]]. He served in the Senate from 1869 to 1875 and again from 1879 to 1881.<ref>{{cite book |last=Heg |first=J. E. |date=1881 |title=Wisconsin Blue Book |url=http://digicoll.library.wisc.edu/cgi-bin/WI/WI-idx?type=turn&entity=WI.WIBlueBk1881.p0543&id=WI.WIBlueBk1881&isize=M |location=Madison, WI |publisher=W. J. Park, State Printer |page=487}}</ref> Recognized as an authority on [[constitutional law]], he made some of the most important legal arguments of 19th-century America. Carpenter presented cases before the [[U. S. Supreme Court]] involving such matters as [[states' rights]] and regulation of [[corporations]].\n \nOriginally a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]], he evolved into a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] during the [[Civil War (United States)|Civil War]], and helped perpetuate the party's political machinery in Wisconsin. His sustained support for President [[Ulysses S. Grant]]'s administration despite allegations of corruption lost him the backing of reformers, and his legal arguments in favor of Democratic candidate [[Samuel J. Tilden]] in the disputed [[presidential election of 1876]] outraged many Republicans. A gifted orator, he was dubbed \"the [[Daniel Webster|Webster]] of the West.\"\n\n==Background and education==\nCarpenter was born in [[Moretown, Vermont]] in the [[Mad River (Vermont)|Mad River]] Valley of the [[Green Mountains|Green Mountain]] range. His pioneering forebears were English, and came to America soon after the [[Pilgrims]]. His grandfather Cephas Carpenter (1770\u20131860)<ref name=\"yb\">{{cite book |date=1896 |title=Year Book of the Wisconsin Society of the Sons of the American Revolution |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bv4QAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA49 |location=Milwaukee, Wis. |publisher=Swain & Tate Company |page=49}}</ref> helped establish Moretown, owned a store, served as a colonel in the militia and took part in the [[War of 1812]].  Cephas Carpenter served in local office including justice of the peace, and though not a member of the bar, possessed wisdom and eloquence that led to a career as an advocate in the local courts.\n\nHis son Ira Carpenter (1798\u20131862)<ref name=\"yb\"/> was chiefly a farmer, but he also gained prominence through positions such as justice of the peace, postmaster and state legislator.\n\nGrandson Merritt displayed intelligence and oratorical talents at an early age, impressing people with his abilities to recite [[Cicero]] and \"exhort\" at religious revivals. He also displayed an aversion to physical work.<ref>Thompson, p.3\u201310</ref> \n\nAfter an explosive argument with a schoolmaster, the 13-year-old Carpenter was expelled from school. He was dissatisfied with the limits of Moretown, and left home to live and study law under the tutelage of family friend (and future Vermont governor) [[Paul Dillingham]] in nearby [[Waterbury (village), Vermont|Waterbury]]. For four years Carpenter attended the local grade school while absorbing Dillingham's law library. Having received an appointment to the [[United States Military Academy]] through Vermont Congressman [[John Mattocks]], Carpenter continued his studies, but he disliked military life and resigned in August 1845, citing poor health.<ref>Thompson, pp. 11-15.</ref>\n\nHe returned to live in Dillingham's home and managed his law office while Dillingham was then a congressman in Washington, D.C. Upon Carpenter's admission to the Vermont bar in November 1847 Dillingham offered to make him his law partner, but Carpenter declined so he could further his law studies under [[Rufus Choate]] of [[Boston]]. Choate was also impressed with Carpenter, and after a few months he too offered him a partnership, but Carpenter sought to make a name and career for himself in the West.<ref>Thompson, pp. 15-21.</ref>\n\n==Wisconsin attorney==\nAfter reading that the territory of Wisconsin had passed its constitution and was soon to become a state, Carpenter chose to migrate west and begin his career as a lawyer in [[Beloit, Wisconsin|Beloit]] on the endorsement of that spot by the New England Emigrating Society's Dr. Horace C. White. Arriving in June 1848, Carpenter quickly established a reputation as a successful and affordable attorney, attracting much acclaim from the local community.\n\nHis practice was interrupted by a painful inflammation of his eyes which rendered him blind. After traveling to New York to seek treatment, his sight gradually recovered after a year as he convalesced in the Waterbury home of his mentor Dillingham. Before returning to Wisconsin he became engaged to Dillingham's daughter Catherine, and they married five years later.<ref>Thompson, pp. 21-29.</ref>\n\nIn 1850 Carpenter returned to resume his law practice in Beloit using a new name, Matthew (Matt) Hale Carpenter, after [[Sir Matthew Hale]], the noted English jurist of the 17th century.<ref>Thompson, pp. 33-34.</ref> Despite an earlier warning from Choate to steer clear of politics, Carpenter successfully ran for [[Rock County, Wisconsin|Rock County]] district attorney, serving from 1850 to 1852 and 1854 to 1856. He was a Democrat in the tradition of [[Thomas Jefferson]] and [[Andrew Jackson]], but he disdained the party's pro-slavery platform while also rejecting [[Whig Party (United States)|Whig Party]] notions of opposing slavery based on \"higher law\"\u2014the idea that individual belief of right and wrong permitted an individual to violate objectionable statutes and ordinances.<ref>Thompson, pp. 31-33.</ref> After appearing to lose a close election for another term as Rock County district attorney in 1854, Carpenter successfully argued that courts could look beyond election board certifications and re-examine voter returns, resulting in the election being overturned.<ref>Thompson, p. 35.</ref>\n\n==''Gardner v. Tisdale''==\nIn 1855 Carpenter discovered that many Beloit residents did not hold legal title to their land because it was sold to them by someone who had [[Pre-emption right|pre-empted]] the land but had not received official title from the government ([[Congress of the United States|Congress]] had previously outlawed the pre-emption of non-agricultural land). Carpenter put forth the theory that the original pre-emptor was still technically the owner of the property.  After several complicated transactions, some of which included Paul Dillingham selling new titles to the landowners, and appeals as far as the [[United States Supreme Court]], which included participation by Dillingham, Rufus Choate, [[Abraham Lincoln]] and other prominent attorneys, Carpenter's legal theory was rejected in a similar case, so the Wisconsin case was withdrawn.<ref>Thompson, pp. 37-39.</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Brown |first=William Fiske |date=1908 |title=Rock County, Wisconsin: A New History |volume=1 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=LUEVAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA2&lpg=PA2&dq=%22Gardner+vs.+Tisdale%22+titles#v=onepage&q=%22Gardner%20vs.%20Tisdale%22%20titles&f=false |location=Chicago, IL |publisher=C. F. Cooper & Co. |pages=157\u2013158}}</ref>\n\n==Barstow-Bashford election dispute==\nWisconsin's gubernatorial election of 1855 was thrown into doubt when incumbent Democratic governor [[William A. Barstow]] was ruled the 157-vote victor over Republican [[Coles Bashford]] by a board of canvassers friendly to Barstow. Discrepancies were discovered in the election returns and political tensions rose as both parties claimed the office and swore in their candidates. Hired by Barstow, Carpenter stalled by repeatedly postponing the case before the [[Wisconsin Supreme Court|state supreme court]]. He claimed that they held no [[jurisdiction]] because elections were matters of the [[Executive branch of the United States|executive branch]], which had ruled Barstow the winner. Nevertheless, the court did claim jurisdiction and the ability to examine election tallies (as Carpenter had previously argued for his own election for district attorney). Barstow then resigned, elevating Lieutenant Governor [[Arthur MacArthur, Sr.|Arthur MacArthur]] to the governorship. After the court ruled that Bashford was the rightful governor, MacArthur gave up the office. Barstow subsequently refused to pay Carpenter his fee.<ref>Thompson, pp. 40-45.</ref>\n\nDespite his defeat Carpenter had demonstrated his legal prowess to the state. A high volume of his cases required his presence in federal court in [[Milwaukee]], leading to him locating his practice there in 1858. He was also coaxed there by Democratic party boss Josiah Noonan, who arranged a law partnership between Carpenter and [[Edward George Ryan|Edward G. Ryan]], another highly regarded attorney and a force in the state Democratic Party. Despite their excellent credentials, they proved to be temperamentally incompatible, and ended their partnership the next year.<ref>Thompson, pp. 46-52.</ref>\n\nBy the time Carpenter moved to Milwaukee he had become adept in the area of railroad litigation and sued many railroads on behalf of investors left holding bonds made worthless by fraudulent manipulation. His debut before the U.S. Supreme Court resulted in his winning a judgment against the La Crosse and Milwaukee Railroad Company.<ref>Thompson, pp. 54-61.</ref> He was also successful as part of a team of lawyers defending abolitionist [[Sherman Booth]] from a charge of rape.<ref>Thompson, pp. 61-62.</ref>\n\n==Loyal Democrat during the Civil War==\nCarpenter supported Democrat Stephen Douglas in the 1860 presidential election, viewing Republican Abraham Lincoln as an honest but incompetent sectional candidate. Yet, he warned those in his party that he saw secession as treason, and he would be \"the first man to raise a musket\" in defense of the Constitution.<ref>Thompson, pp. 62-63.</ref> Following the Confederates' attack on Fort Sumter in 1861, Carpenter did not enlist but became a rousing speaker in support of the Union cause.<ref>Thompson, p. 65.</ref>\n\nWhile he saw that many federal actions would be unconstitutional in peacetime, he reasoned that arbitrary arrests and suspensions of ''[[habeas corpus]]'' were acts of self-preservation during wartime and thereby permitted.<ref>Thompson, pp. 64-65.</ref> He also became an early advocate for emancipation, but only as a war measure rather than an act of humanity.<ref>Thompson, p. 66.</ref> Excluded from meetings of the Democratic leadership, Carpenter joined other like-minded party members of the \"Loyal Democracy\" in considering a third party in Wisconsin, but nothing came of it.<ref>Thompson, pp. 72-78.</ref>\n\nPersonal letters he had written saying Lincoln was \"idiotic\" found their way into newspapers, but Carpenter supported him for re-election in 1864 by making numerous pro-Union and pro-Lincoln speeches.<ref>Thompson, pp. 79-82.</ref>\n\n==Defining the Reconstruction Acts==\nCarpenter was the key attorney in a series of landmark cases before the U.S. Supreme Court which helped define states' rights by determining the legality of the [[Reconstruction Acts|Reconstruction acts]] passed by Congress.\n\n''[[Ex parte Garland]]'' dealt with the disbarment from federal courts of Southern lawyers who refused to take an oath swearing they had not taken up arms or assisted the Confederacy. Carpenter argued that the act passed on January 24, 1865 was [[ex post facto]] (the war had since ended) and a [[bill of attainder]] (it punished without a trial). In December 1865 the court upheld his argument with the majority opinion employing phrases from Carpenter's brief.<ref>Thompson, pp. 89-90.</ref>\n\n''[[Ex parte McCardle]]'' concerned the legal authority of the occupying Union Army. Confederate Colonel William L. McCardle, the editor of the ''Vicksburg Times'', was charged with defying military authority by inciting rebellion, libeling federal officials, and intimidating voters. After the circuit court denied him a writ of [[habeas corpus]], McCardle appealed to the Supreme Court. Carpenter argued that the court lacked jurisdiction over a president's official acts, as in a similar case of his, ''Georgia vs. Grant''. Rather than claiming the Union's \"[[right of conquest]],\" Carpenter said the Southern states had surrendered their constitutional protections when they had seceded, essentially reverting to territories.<ref>Thompson, pp. 91-98.</ref>\n\nAfter he concluded his eloquent arguments, Secretary of War [[Edwin Stanton]] hugged him, declaring \"Carpenter, you have saved us!\" Even McCardle's attorney [[Jeremiah S. Black]] lauded him as \"the first Constitutional lawyer in the country.\" However, [[Radical Republicans]] in Congress feared that the reconstruction acts would be ruled unconstitutional, so they quickly pushed through a law repealing the Habeas Corpus Act of 1867, barring jurisdiction in pending cases and preventing a clear decision from being rendered by the court.<ref>Thompson, pp. 98-99.</ref>\n\nIn the [[Slaughterhouse cases]] Carpenter represented the Crescent City Livestock Landing and Slaughterhouse Company, which had been granted a monopoly on all slaughterhouse business in [[New Orleans]] by the [[carpetbagger|carpetbag]] state legislature of [[Louisiana]] in 1869. Butchers and cattle dealers thrown out of work by the law obtained an injunction from a district court, claiming they had been denied [[equal protection]] under the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourteenth Amendment]] and deprived of property under the due process clause. Making a plea for states' rights, Carpenter contended that the amendment had been intended solely to elevate African Americans and had no bearing on economic statutes passed by a state. He also warned of too many powers being centralized in the federal government. The court concurred in Carpenter's narrowing of the scope of the Fourteenth Amendment.<ref>Thompson, pp. 100-102.</ref>\n\nIn ''[[Bradwell vs. Illinois]]'', Carpenter sought to broaden the amendment's protections in the case of the editor of the [[Chicago]] ''Legal News'', [[Myra Bradwell]], who had been denied admission to the bar of the [[Illinois Supreme Court]] because she was a woman. Representing Bradwell, Carpenter argued that no class of people could be excluded from practicing the legal profession. The federal court disagreed, questioning the propriety of ruling on a state's qualifications for admission to the bar.<ref>Thompson, pp. 102-103.</ref>\n\nThese cases brought Carpenter handsome fees, national acclaim, and much derision from the losing factions. He'd also won the support of Stanton and President [[Ulysses S. Grant]], who both urged him to run as a Republican for the U.S. Senate.<ref>Thompson, p. 99.</ref>\n\n==Republican senator==\nFollowing the Civil War Carpenter's transformation from a [[Jeffersonian democracy|Jeffersonian Democrat]] into a Republican was complete. Despite reports that he backed [[President Andrew Johnson]]'s policies, he made speeches supporting the Radical congress. He called for the enfranchisement of African-American men and invited members of the Loyal Democracy to join the Republicans, as he himself did in the summer of 1867 with his support for Governor [[Lucius Fairchild]]'s re-election.\n\nWith high-profile backing Carpenter ran successfully for the senate seat occupied by [[James R. Doolittle]], a \"Johnsonized\" Republican who had fallen out of favor with his party.<ref>Thompson, pp. 105-117.</ref> With his victory he solidified his status with the \"Madison Regency,\" a Republican group that included former governor and Johnson's Postmaster General [[Alexander Randall]], Madison postmaster [[Elisha W. Keyes]] and ''[[Wisconsin State Journal]]'' editor and Republican state central committee chairman [[Horace Rublee]].<ref>Thompson, p. 112.</ref> After Rublee was appointed minister to [[Switzerland]] by President Grant, Keyes became party chairman and closely coordinated with Carpenter to distribute federal patronage jobs to political allies.\n\nOnce in the Senate, Carpenter moderated his views to the degree that he became one of the spokesmen of the emerging Stalwart Republicans. He opposed any \"fundamental conditions\" placed on states wishing to be readmitted to the Union, and favored blanket amnesty for former Confederates.<ref>Thompson, pp. 133-138.</ref> Carpenter was known as one of the staunchest supporters of the corrupt Grant administration.<ref>Thompson, pp. 148-149.</ref> In the Senate he presented an unabashed defense of political patronage, mocking the idea of civil service reform.<ref>Thompson, pp. 156-160.</ref> He also feuded with [[Liberal Republican Party (United States)|Liberal Republican]] senators [[Charles Sumner]] and [[Carl Schurz]] over many issues. He delivered a sarcastic denunciation of Sumner's wide-reaching civil rights amendment to the Confederate amnesty bill.<ref>Thompson, pp. 160-164.</ref> As the chair of an investigating committee he also debunked Sumner and Schurz's claim that the War Department had broken its neutrality when it sold outmoded rifles to [[France]] during the [[Franco-Prussian War]].<ref>Thompson, pp. 166-171.</ref> Despite such skirmishes Carpenter was a respected figure in the senate, being elected president pro tempore by his colleagues in 1871. He also served as chairman of the Committee on Enrolled Bills ([[42nd United States Congress|42nd Congress]]) and the Committee to Audit and Control the Contingent Expense (42nd and [[43rd United States Congress|43rd Congresses]]).\n\nAs part of another committee inquiry, Carpenter went to [[Louisiana]] to investigate election claims in order to determine the rightful governor of the contested state. His report was highly critical of both factions, but he urged the recognition of Republican governor [[William P. Kellogg]].<ref>Thompson, pp. 178-191.</ref> Years later Carpenter's impartiality was called into question when personal letters revealed a close relationship between the two, including a \"desperately short\" Carpenter asking Kellogg for a $1,000 loan.<ref>Thompson, pp. 222-223.</ref>\n\n==Drawing fire from press and party==\nAs Carpenter's influence grew within the Grant administration, so did the condemnations from the press. One of his Senate investigations resulted in two journalists being jailed for not divulging the source of a leaked treaty.<ref>Thompson, pp. 149-154.</ref> Opposition newspapers like the ''[[New York Tribune]]'' responded by not only criticizing Carpenter's methods, but by also condemning his moral character by bringing his private life into question.<ref>Thompson, pp. 200-202.</ref> Later in his term editors accused Carpenter of trying to effectively \"gag\" newspapers by advancing a bill that would allow judicial process to be served upon the agents (i.e. interviewers) of persons involved in civil suits.<ref>Thompson, pp. 215-216.</ref>\n\nIn 1873 Carpenter angered many in his own party by taking positions that ran counter to the stalwart doctrine. In a spirit of reform he boldly owned up to administration excesses such as the [[Cr\u00e9dit Mobilier of America scandal|Credit Mobilier]] and the \"Salary Grab,\" defending them in a speech in [[Janesville, Wisconsin|Janesville]].<ref>Thompson, pp. 193-198.</ref> In a speech at [[Ripon, Wisconsin|Ripon]] he denounced the railroads, insisting they were public highways paid for with government land grants. He also stated his belief that the government has a right as well as a duty to regulate corporations.<ref>Thompson, pp. 221-222.</ref>\n\nWishing to make the ''[[Milwaukee Sentinel]]'' into a more reliable organ for the state Republican party, Carpenter and other backers bought the paper and forced out editor [[Alexander M. Thomson]], who had been instrumental in getting Carpenter elected senator. Thomson was now deemed too critical of the party machine. His ousting made him a lifelong enemy of Carpenter. The ''Sentinel'' soon was seen as Carpenter's personal mouthpiece.<ref>Thompson, pp. 205-207</ref>\n\nDespite the incessant criticism, Carpenter was seen as being easily re-elected in 1875. Nevertheless, a surprise bolt by disgruntled Republicans combined with votes by calculating Democrats resulted in the election of [[Angus Cameron (American politician)|Angus Cameron]], a [[La Crosse, Wisconsin|La Crosse]] Republican.<ref>Thompson, pp. 218-230</ref>\n\n==Out of office and under scrutiny==\nIn 1875 Carpenter was implicated in the [[Whiskey Ring]] scandal that funneled federal liquor tax revenues to some states' Republican parties. Although he was close to key participants in the Milwaukee ring, no evidence emerged to prove his involvement.<ref>Thompson, pp. 233-242</ref>\n\nDuring this time he was also defending Grant's Secretary of War [[William W. Belknap]] against [[Trader post scandal|charges]] that he had accepted money in exchange for the appointment of a post trader. Despite Belknap's immediate resignation outraged House Democrats proceeded with his impeachment. Carpenter portrayed Belknap as the hapless victim of a social-climbing wife, but his legal victory relied on his assertion that jurisdiction over Belknap ended with his resignation.<ref>Thompson, pp. 243-246</ref>\n\nAlso in 1875 Carpenter was defense counsel for officials of the [[Miners\u2019 National Association]] (MNA) in an important labor case that sought to apply the legal concept of conspiracy to union picketing and organization efforts. The case grew out of a coal miners' strike in [[Clearfield County, Pennsylvania]] which was supported by the MNA, then numerically one of the largest American trade unions. First over fifty of the striking workers were tried upon a charge of criminal conspiracy and thirty-six of them were convicted with some sentenced to jail, although they appeared to have been guilty of no more than peaceful picketing. Then [[John Siney]], the president of the MNA, and Xingo Parks, one of the union\u2019s best organizers, were tried on the same charge. Siney was acquitted, but Parks convicted, although pardoned shortly thereafter.<ref>Witte, Edwin E., Early American Labor Cases, 35 Yale Law Journal 7, 1926, pp. 830-31</ref>\n\nFollowing the disputed presidential election of 1876, Carpenter was hired by supporters of the Democratic candidate [[Samuel J. Tilden]] to examine Louisiana's vote counts and argue for victory over Republican [[Rutherford B. Hayes]]. Carpenter's first-hand accounts of the corrupt Republican state administration gave the Democrats some reason for hope, but ultimately the partisan make-up of the special electoral commission (7 Republicans, 6 Democrats) and its refusal to look behind the certified counts made many of their rulings a forgone conclusive win for Hayes.<ref>Thompson, pp. 247-253</ref>\n\n==Return to the senate==\nDespite ongoing press criticism and declining health, in 1878 Carpenter launched a bid for the senate seat occupied by Republican [[Timothy Howe]]. With the help of a strong lobby, he won over enough votes in the legislature to prevail over state party boss (and former friend) Elisha W. Keyes.<ref>Thompson, pp. 254-264</ref>\n\nCarpenter's second term as senator lacked the political drama of his Reconstruction years. He spoke in favor of President [[Rutherford B. Hayes]]'s maintenance of federal troops at southern polling places. He also vigorously opposed the Democrats' proposed pardoning of General [[Fitz-John Porter]] for ignoring General [[John Pope (military officer)|John Pope]]'s orders at [[Manassas]] in 1863, arguing that the power of pardon resides solely with the president.<ref>Thompson, pp. 264-266</ref> Carpenter remained a loyal supporter of President Grant in his quest for a third term, igniting bitter debates between Carpenter and White House aspirant Senator [[James G. Blaine]] of Maine.<ref>Thompson, pp. 268-270.</ref>\n\n==Death==\nWhile Carpenter's evident declining health was attributed to his indulgent lifestyle, he also suffered from the lung congestion of [[Bright's disease]]. After a cycle of relapses and recoveries he died on February 24, 1881 at his Washington, D.C. home surrounded by friends and family. He was buried at Forest Home Cemetery in Milwaukee.<ref>Thompson, pp. 275-280.</ref>\n\n==Family==\nIn 1855 Carpenter married Caroline Dillingham, the daughter of Paul Dillingham.<ref>{{cite book |last=Huse |first=Hiram A. |title=A Memorial Sketch of Paul Dillingham: Officers and Members: Report of Proceedings of the Annual Meeting |volume=3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=99o8AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA77 |location=Montpelier, VT |publisher=Argus and Patriot Book and Job Printing |page=77|year=1892 }}</ref> They were the parents of four children.  Daughters Ada and Annie were born and died in 1860.<ref>Thompson, p.294</ref> The other two lived to adulthood\u2014a daughter named Lilian (1857\u20131942)<ref>Thompson{{page needed|date=February 2018}}</ref> and a son named Paul Dillingham Carpenter (1867\u20131932).<ref>Thompson{{page needed|date=February 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"yb\"/>  Paul D. Carpenter was an attorney in Milwaukee and also served as judge of the county court.<ref>{{cite book |last=Campbell |first=John A. |date=1902 |title=A Biographical History, with Portraits, of Prominent Men of the Great West |url=https://archive.org/details/biographicalhist00camp |location=Chicago, IL |publisher=Western Biographical and Engraving Co. |pages=[https://archive.org/details/biographicalhist00camp/page/221 221]\u2013222}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of United States Congress members who died in office (1790\u20131899)]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book |last=Thompson |first=E. Bruce |year=1954 |title=Matthew Hale Carpenter: Webster of the West |url=http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.b3288429;view=1up;seq=11 |location=Madison, Wis. |publisher=State Historical Society of Wisconsin}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [[Frank A. Flower|Flower, Frank A.]] ''[https://archive.org/details/lifematthewhale00flowgoog/page/n61 <!-- pg=1 --> Life of Matthew Hale Carpenter]''. Madison, Wis.: David Atwood & Co., 1883.\n* ''[https://archive.org/details/memorialaddress06addrgoog/page/n21 <!-- pg=1 --> Memorial Addresses on the Life and Character of Matthew H. Carpenter, A Senator from Wisconsin]''. Washington, DC: U.S. Government Printing Office, 1882.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{CongBio|C000171}}\n*{{Findagrave|6854506}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-sen}}\n{{U.S. Senator box\n | state = Wisconsin\n | class = 1\n | before = [[James Rood Doolittle|James R. Doolittle]]\n | after = [[Angus Cameron (American politician)|Angus Cameron]]\n | alongside = [[Timothy O. Howe]]\n | years = March 4, 1869 \u2013 March 3, 1875}}\n{{succession box\n | title = [[President pro tempore of the United States Senate]]\n | before = [[Henry B. Anthony]]\n | years = March 12, 1873 \u2013 January 4, 1875\n | after = [[Henry B. Anthony]]}}\n{{U.S. Senator box\n | state = Wisconsin\n | class = 3\n | before = [[Timothy O. Howe]]\n | after = [[Angus Cameron (American politician)|Angus Cameron]]\n | alongside = [[Angus Cameron (American politician)|Angus Cameron]]\n | years = March 4, 1879 \u2013 February 24, 1881}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{USSenWI}}\n{{USSenPresProTemp}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Carpenter, Matthew H.}}\n[[Category:1824 births]]\n[[Category:1881 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Moretown, Vermont]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Beloit, Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Milwaukee]]\n[[Category:United States Military Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:United States senators from Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts lawyers]]\n[[Category:Vermont lawyers]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Wisconsin lawyers]]\n[[Category:Wisconsin Republicans]]\n[[Category:Republican Party United States senators]]\n[[Category:Burials in Wisconsin]]\n[[Category:Wisconsin Democrats]]\n[[Category:People of Wisconsin in the American Civil War]]\n[[Category:American militia officers]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Presidents pro tempore of the United States Senate]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Officeholder\n|name          = Matthew Hale Carpenter\n|image         = Matthew H. Carpenter - Brady-Handy.jpg\n|office        = [[President pro tempore of the United States Senate]]\n|term_start    = March 12, 1873\n|term_end      = January 4, 1875\n|predecessor   = [[Henry B. Anthony]]\n|successor     = [[Henry B. Anthony]]\n|jr/sr1         = United States Senator\n|state1         = [[Wisconsin]]\n|term_start1   = March 4, 1879\n|term_end1     = February 24, 1881\n|predecessor1  = [[Timothy O. Howe]]\n|successor1    = [[Angus Cameron (American politician)|Angus Cameron]]\n|term_start2   = March 4, 1869\n|term_end2     = March 3, 1875\n|predecessor2  = [[James Rood Doolittle|James R. Doolittle]]\n|successor2    = [[Angus Cameron (American politician)|Angus Cameron]]\n|birth_date    = {{birth date|1824|12|22}}\n|birth_place   = [[Moretown, Vermont]]\n|death_date    = {{death date and age|1881|2|24|1824|12|22}}\n|death_place   = [[Washington, D.C.]]\n|resting_place = [[Forest Home Cemetery]], [[Milwaukee, Wisconsin]]\n|party         = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|alma_mater    = [[United States Military Academy]] (attended)\n|education     = Studied law with [[Paul Dillingham]] and [[Rufus Choate]]\n|profession    = Attorney\n|spouse        = Caroline Dillingham Carpenter (m. 1855)\n|children      = 2\n|relations     = [[Paul Dillingham]] (father in law)<br/>[[William P. Dillingham]] (brother in law)\n}}\n'''Matthew Hale Carpenter''' (born Decatur Merritt Hammond Carpenter; December 22, 1824 \u2013 February 24, 1881) was an American attorney and U.S. Senator representing the state of [[Wisconsin]]. He served in the Senate from 1869 to 1875 and again from 1879 to 1881.<ref>{{cite book |last=Heg |first=J. E. |date=1881 |title=Wisconsin Blue Book |url=http://digicoll.library.wisc.edu/cgi-bin/WI/WI-idx?type=turn&entity=WI.WIBlueBk1881.p0543&id=WI.WIBlueBk1881&isize=M |location=Madison, WI |publisher=W. J. Park, State Printer |page=487}}</ref> Recognized as an authority on [[constitutional law]], he made some of the most important legal arguments of 19th-century America. Carpenter presented cases before the [[U. S. Supreme Court]] involving such matters as [[states' rights]] and regulation of [[corporations]].\n \nOriginally a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]], he evolved into a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] during the [[Civil War (United States)|Civil War]], and helped perpetuate the party's political machinery in Wisconsin. His sustained support for President [[Ulysses S. Grant]]'s administration despite allegations of corruption lost him the backing of reformers, and his legal arguments in favor of Democratic candidate [[Samuel J. Tilden]] in the disputed [[presidential election of 1876]] outraged many Republicans. A gifted orator, he was dubbed \"the [[Daniel Webster|Webster]] of the West.\"\n\n==Background and education==\nCarpenter was born in [[Moretown, Vermont]] in the [[Mad River (Vermont)|Mad River]] Valley of the [[Green Mountains|Green Mountain]] range. His pioneering forebears were English, and came to America soon after the [[Pilgrims]]. His grandfather Cephas Carpenter (1770\u20131860)<ref name=\"yb\">{{cite book |date=1896 |title=Year Book of the Wisconsin Society of the Sons of the American Revolution |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bv4QAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA49 |location=Milwaukee, Wis. |publisher=Swain & Tate Company |page=49}}</ref> helped establish Moretown, owned a store, served as a colonel in the militia and took part in the [[War of 1812]].  Cephas Carpenter served in local office including justice of the peace, and though not a member of the bar, possessed wisdom and eloquence that led to a career as an advocate in the local courts.\n\nHis son Ira Carpenter (1798\u20131862)<ref name=\"yb\"/> was chiefly a farmer, but he also gained prominence through positions such as justice of the peace, postmaster and state legislator.\n\nGrandson Merritt displayed intelligence and oratorical talents at an early age, impressing people with his abilities to recite [[Cicero]] and \"exhort\" at religious revivals. He also displayed an aversion to physical work.<ref>Thompson, p.3\u201310</ref> \n\nAfter an explosive argument with a schoolmaster, the 13-year-old Carpenter was expelled from school. He was dissatisfied with the limits of Moretown, and left home to live and study law under the tutelage of family friend (and future Vermont governor) [[Paul Dillingham]] in nearby [[Waterbury (village), Vermont|Waterbury]]. For four years Carpenter attended the local grade school while absorbing Dillingham's law library. Having received an appointment to the [[United States Military Academy]] through Vermont Congressman [[John Mattocks]], Carpenter continued his studies, but he disliked military life and resigned in August 1845, citing poor health.<ref>Thompson, pp. 11-15.</ref>\n\nHe returned to live in Dillingham's home and managed his law office while Dillingham was then a congressman in Washington, D.C. Upon Carpenter's admission to the Vermont bar in November 1847 Dillingham offered to make him his law partner, but Carpenter declined so he could further his law studies under [[Rufus Choate]] of [[Boston]]. Choate was also impressed with Carpenter, and after a few months he too offered him a partnership, but Carpenter sought to make a name and career for himself in the West.<ref>Thompson, pp. 15-21.</ref>\n\n==Wisconsin attorney==\nAfter reading that the territory of Wisconsin had passed its constitution and was soon to become a state, Carpenter chose to migrate west and begin his career as a lawyer in [[Beloit, Wisconsin|Beloit]] on the endorsement of that spot by the New England Emigrating Society's Dr. Horace C. White. Arriving in June 1848, Carpenter quickly established a reputation as a successful and affordable attorney, attracting much acclaim from the local community.\n\nHis practice was interrupted by a painful inflammation of his eyes which rendered him blind. After traveling to New York to seek treatment, his sight gradually recovered after a year as he convalesced in the Waterbury home of his mentor Dillingham. Before returning to Wisconsin he became engaged to Dillingham's daughter Catherine, and they married five years later.<ref>Thompson, pp. 21-29.</ref>\n\nIn 1850 Carpenter returned to resume his law practice in Beloit using a new name, Matthew (Matt) Hale Carpenter, after [[Sir Matthew Hale]], the noted English jurist of the 17th century.<ref>Thompson, pp. 33-34.</ref> Despite an earlier warning from Choate to steer clear of politics, Carpenter successfully ran for [[Rock County, Wisconsin|Rock County]] district attorney, serving from 1850 to 1852 and 1854 to 1856. He was a Democrat in the tradition of [[Thomas Jefferson]] and [[Andrew Jackson]], but he disdained the party's pro-slavery platform while also rejecting [[Whig Party (United States)|Whig Party]] notions of opposing slavery based on \"higher law\"\u2014the idea that individual belief of right and wrong permitted an individual to violate objectionable statutes and ordinances.<ref>Thompson, pp. 31-33.</ref> After appearing to lose a close election for another term as Rock County district attorney in 1854, Carpenter successfully argued that courts could look beyond election board certifications and re-examine voter returns, resulting in the election being overturned.<ref>Thompson, p. 35.</ref>\n\n==''Gardner v. Tisdale''==\nIn 1855 Carpenter discovered that many Beloit residents did not hold legal title to their land because it was sold to them by someone who had [[Pre-emption right|pre-empted]] the land but had not received official title from the government ([[Congress of the United States|Congress]] had previously outlawed the pre-emption of non-agricultural land). Carpenter put forth the theory that the original pre-emptor was still technically the owner of the property.  After several complicated transactions, some of which included Paul Dillingham selling new titles to the landowners, and appeals as far as the [[United States Supreme Court]], which included participation by Dillingham, Rufus Choate, [[Abraham Lincoln]] and other prominent attorneys, Carpenter's legal theory was rejected in a similar case, so the Wisconsin case was withdrawn.<ref>Thompson, pp. 37-39.</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Brown |first=William Fiske |date=1908 |title=Rock County, Wisconsin: A New History |volume=1 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=LUEVAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA2&lpg=PA2&dq=%22Gardner+vs.+Tisdale%22+titles#v=onepage&q=%22Gardner%20vs.%20Tisdale%22%20titles&f=false |location=Chicago, IL |publisher=C. F. Cooper & Co. |pages=157\u2013158}}</ref>\n\n==Barstow-Bashford election dispute==\nWisconsin's gubernatorial election of 1855 was thrown into doubt when incumbent Democratic governor [[William A. Barstow]] was ruled the 157-vote victor over Republican [[Coles Bashford]] by a board of canvassers friendly to Barstow. Discrepancies were discovered in the election returns and political tensions rose as both parties claimed the office and swore in their candidates. Hired by Barstow, Carpenter stalled by repeatedly postponing the case before the [[Wisconsin Supreme Court|state supreme court]]. He claimed that they held no [[jurisdiction]] because elections were matters of the [[Executive branch of the United States|executive branch]], which had ruled Barstow the winner. Nevertheless, the court did claim jurisdiction and the ability to examine election tallies (as Carpenter had previously argued for his own election for district attorney). Barstow then resigned, elevating Lieutenant Governor [[Arthur MacArthur, Sr.|Arthur MacArthur]] to the governorship. After the court ruled that Bashford was the rightful governor, MacArthur gave up the office. Barstow subsequently refused to pay Carpenter his fee.<ref>Thompson, pp. 40-45.</ref>\n\nDespite his defeat Carpenter had demonstrated his legal prowess to the state. A high volume of his cases required his presence in federal court in [[Milwaukee]], leading to him locating his practice there in 1858. He was also coaxed there by Democratic party boss Josiah Noonan, who arranged a law partnership between Carpenter and [[Edward George Ryan|Edward G. Ryan]], another highly regarded attorney and a force in the state Democratic Party. Despite their excellent credentials, they proved to be temperamentally incompatible, and ended their partnership the next year.<ref>Thompson, pp. 46-52.</ref>\n\nBy the time Carpenter moved to Milwaukee he had become adept in the area of railroad litigation and sued many railroads on behalf of investors left holding bonds made worthless by fraudulent manipulation. His debut before the U.S. Supreme Court resulted in his winning a judgment against the La Crosse and Milwaukee Railroad Company.<ref>Thompson, pp. 54-61.</ref> He was also successful as part of a team of lawyers defending abolitionist [[Sherman Booth]] from a charge of rape.<ref>Thompson, pp. 61-62.</ref>\n\n==Loyal Democrat during the Civil War==\nCarpenter supported Democrat Stephen Douglas in the 1860 presidential election, viewing Republican Abraham Lincoln as an honest but incompetent sectional candidate. Yet, he warned those in his party that he saw secession as treason, and he would be \"the first man to raise a musket\" in defense of the Constitution.<ref>Thompson, pp. 62-63.</ref> Following the Confederates' attack on Fort Sumter in 1861, Carpenter did not enlist but became a rousing speaker in support of the Union cause.<ref>Thompson, p. 65.</ref>\n\nWhile he saw that many federal actions would be unconstitutional in peacetime, he reasoned that arbitrary arrests and suspensions of ''[[habeas corpus]]'' were acts of self-preservation during wartime and thereby permitted.<ref>Thompson, pp. 64-65.</ref> He also became an early advocate for emancipation, but only as a war measure rather than an act of humanity.<ref>Thompson, p. 66.</ref> Excluded from meetings of the Democratic leadership, Carpenter joined other like-minded party members of the \"Loyal Democracy\" in considering a third party in Wisconsin, but nothing came of it.<ref>Thompson, pp. 72-78.</ref>\n\nPersonal letters he had written saying Lincoln was \"idiotic\" found their way into newspapers, but Carpenter supported him for re-election in 1864 by making numerous pro-Union and pro-Lincoln speeches.<ref>Thompson, pp. 79-82.</ref>\n\n==Defining the Reconstruction Acts==\nCarpenter was the key attorney in a series of landmark cases before the U.S. Supreme Court which helped define states' rights by determining the legality of the [[Reconstruction Acts|Reconstruction acts]] passed by Congress.\n\n''[[Ex parte Garland]]'' dealt with the disbarment from federal courts of Southern lawyers who refused to take an oath swearing they had not taken up arms or assisted the Confederacy. Carpenter argued that the act passed on January 24, 1865 was [[ex post facto]] (the war had since ended) and a [[bill of attainder]] (it punished without a trial). In December 1865 the court upheld his argument with the majority opinion employing phrases from Carpenter's brief.<ref>Thompson, pp. 89-90.</ref>\n\n''[[Ex parte McCardle]]'' concerned the legal authority of the occupying Union Army. Confederate Colonel William L. McCardle, the editor of the ''Vicksburg Times'', was charged with defying military authority by inciting rebellion, libeling federal officials, and intimidating voters. After the circuit court denied him a writ of [[habeas corpus]], McCardle appealed to the Supreme Court. Carpenter argued that the court lacked jurisdiction over a president's official acts, as in a similar case of his, ''Georgia vs. Grant''. Rather than claiming the Union's \"[[right of conquest]],\" Carpenter said the Southern states had surrendered their constitutional protections when they had seceded, essentially reverting to territories.<ref>Thompson, pp. 91-98.</ref>\n\nAfter he concluded his eloquent arguments, Secretary of War [[Edwin Stanton]] hugged him, declaring \"Carpenter, you have saved us!\" Even McCardle's attorney [[Jeremiah S. Black]] lauded him as \"the first Constitutional lawyer in the country.\" However, [[Radical Republicans]] in Congress feared that the reconstruction acts would be ruled unconstitutional, so they quickly pushed through a law repealing the Habeas Corpus Act of 1867, barring jurisdiction in pending cases and preventing a clear decision from being rendered by the court.<ref>Thompson, pp. 98-99.</ref>\n\nIn the [[Slaughterhouse cases]] Carpenter represented the Crescent City Livestock Landing and Slaughterhouse Company, which had been granted a monopoly on all slaughterhouse business in [[New Orleans]] by the [[carpetbagger|carpetbag]] state legislature of [[Louisiana]] in 1869. Butchers and cattle dealers thrown out of work by the law obtained an injunction from a district court, claiming they had been denied [[equal protection]] under the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourteenth Amendment]] and deprived of property under the due process clause. Making a plea for states' rights, Carpenter contended that the amendment had been intended solely to elevate African Americans and had no bearing on economic statutes passed by a state. He also warned of too many powers being centralized in the federal government. The court concurred in Carpenter's narrowing of the scope of the Fourteenth Amendment.<ref>Thompson, pp. 100-102.</ref>\n\nIn ''[[Bradwell vs. Illinois]]'', Carpenter sought to broaden the amendment's protections in the case of the editor of the [[Chicago]] ''Legal News'', [[Myra Bradwell]], who had been denied admission to the bar of the [[Illinois Supreme Court]] because she was a woman. Representing Bradwell, Carpenter argued that no class of people could be excluded from practicing the legal profession. The federal court disagreed, questioning the propriety of ruling on a state's qualifications for admission to the bar.<ref>Thompson, pp. 102-103.</ref>\n\nThese cases brought Carpenter handsome fees, national acclaim, and much derision from the losing factions. He'd also won the support of Stanton and President [[Ulysses S. Grant]], who both urged him to run as a Republican for the U.S. Senate.<ref>Thompson, p. 99.</ref>\n\n==Republican senator==\nFollowing the Civil War Carpenter's transformation from a [[Jeffersonian democracy|Jeffersonian Democrat]] into a Republican was complete. Despite reports that he backed [[President Andrew Johnson]]'s policies, he made speeches supporting the Radical congress. He called for the enfranchisement of African-American men and invited members of the Loyal Democracy to join the Republicans, as he himself did in the summer of 1867 with his support for Governor [[Lucius Fairchild]]'s re-election.\n\nWith high-profile backing Carpenter ran successfully for the senate seat occupied by [[James R. Doolittle]], a \"Johnsonized\" Republican who had fallen out of favor with his party.<ref>Thompson, pp. 105-117.</ref> With his victory he solidified his status with the \"Madison Regency,\" a Republican group that included former governor and Johnson's Postmaster General [[Alexander Randall]], Madison postmaster [[Elisha W. Keyes]] and ''[[Wisconsin State Journal]]'' editor and Republican state central committee chairman [[Horace Rublee]].<ref>Thompson, p. 112.</ref> After Rublee was appointed minister to [[Switzerland]] by President Grant, Keyes became party chairman and closely coordinated with Carpenter to distribute federal patronage jobs to political allies.\n\nOnce in the Senate, Carpenter moderated his views to the degree that he became one of the spokesmen of the emerging Stalwart Republicans. He opposed any \"fundamental conditions\" placed on states wishing to be readmitted to the Union, and favored blanket amnesty for former Confederates.<ref>Thompson, pp. 133-138.</ref> Carpenter was known as one of the staunchest supporters of the corrupt Grant administration.<ref>Thompson, pp. 148-149.</ref> In the Senate he presented an unabashed defense of political patronage, mocking the idea of civil service reform.<ref>Thompson, pp. 156-160.</ref> He also feuded with [[Liberal Republican Party (United States)|Liberal Republican]] senators [[Charles Sumner]] and [[Carl Schurz]] over many issues. He delivered a sarcastic denunciation of Sumner's wide-reaching civil rights amendment to the Confederate amnesty bill.<ref>Thompson, pp. 160-164.</ref> As the chair of an investigating committee he also debunked Sumner and Schurz's claim that the War Department had broken its neutrality when it sold outmoded rifles to [[France]] during the [[Franco-Prussian War]].<ref>Thompson, pp. 166-171.</ref> Despite such skirmishes Carpenter was a respected figure in the senate, being elected president pro tempore by his colleagues in 1871. He also served as chairman of the Committee on Enrolled Bills ([[42nd United States Congress|42nd Congress]]) and the Committee to Audit and Control the Contingent Expense (42nd and [[43rd United States Congress|43rd Congresses]]).\n\nAs part of another committee inquiry, Carpenter went to [[Louisiana]] to investigate election claims in order to determine the rightful governor of the contested state. His report was highly critical of both factions, but he urged the recognition of Republican governor [[William P. Kellogg]].<ref>Thompson, pp. 178-191.</ref> Years later Carpenter's impartiality was called into question when personal letters revealed a close relationship between the two, including a \"desperately short\" Carpenter asking Kellogg for a $1,000 loan.<ref>Thompson, pp. 222-223.</ref>\n\n==Drawing fire from press and party==\nAs Carpenter's influence grew within the Grant administration, so did the condemnations from the press. One of his Senate investigations resulted in two journalists being jailed for not divulging the source of a leaked treaty.<ref>Thompson, pp. 149-154.</ref> Opposition newspapers like the ''[[New York Tribune]]'' responded by not only criticizing Carpenter's methods, but by also condemning his moral character by bringing his private life into question.<ref>Thompson, pp. 200-202.</ref> Later in his term editors accused Carpenter of trying to effectively \"gag\" newspapers by advancing a bill that would allow judicial process to be served upon the agents (i.e. interviewers) of persons involved in civil suits.<ref>Thompson, pp. 215-216.</ref>\n\nIn 1873 Carpenter angered many in his own party by taking positions that ran counter to the stalwart doctrine. In a spirit of reform he boldly owned up to administration excesses such as the [[Cr\u00e9dit Mobilier of America scandal|Credit Mobilier]] and the \"Salary Grab,\" defending them in a speech in [[Janesville, Wisconsin|Janesville]].<ref>Thompson, pp. 193-198.</ref> In a speech at [[Ripon, Wisconsin|Ripon]] he denounced the railroads, insisting they were public highways paid for with government land grants. He also stated his belief that the government has a right as well as a duty to regulate corporations.<ref>Thompson, pp. 221-222.</ref>\n\nWishing to make the ''[[Milwaukee Sentinel]]'' into a more reliable organ for the state Republican party, Carpenter and other backers bought the paper and forced out editor [[Alexander M. Thomson]], who had been instrumental in getting Carpenter elected senator. Thomson was now deemed too critical of the party machine. His ousting made him a lifelong enemy of Carpenter. The ''Sentinel'' soon was seen as Carpenter's personal mouthpiece.<ref>Thompson, pp. 205-207</ref>\n\nDespite the incessant criticism, Carpenter was seen as being easily re-elected in 1875. Nevertheless, a surprise bolt by disgruntled Republicans combined with votes by calculating Democrats resulted in the election of [[Angus Cameron (American politician)|Angus Cameron]], a [[La Crosse, Wisconsin|La Crosse]] Republican.<ref>Thompson, pp. 218-230</ref>\n\n==Out of office and under scrutiny==\nIn 1875 Carpenter was implicated in the [[Whiskey Ring]] scandal that funneled federal liquor tax revenues to some states' Republican parties. Although he was close to key participants in the Milwaukee ring, no evidence emerged to prove his involvement.<ref>Thompson, pp. 233-242</ref>\n\nDuring this time he was also defending Grant's Secretary of War [[William W. Belknap]] against [[Trader post scandal|charges]] that he had accepted money in exchange for the appointment of a post trader. Despite Belknap's immediate resignation outraged House Democrats proceeded with his impeachment. Carpenter portrayed Belknap as the hapless victim of a social-climbing wife, but his legal victory relied on his assertion that jurisdiction over Belknap ended with his resignation.<ref>Thompson, pp. 243-246</ref>\n\nAlso in 1875 Carpenter was defense counsel for officials of the [[Miners\u2019 National Association]] (MNA) in an important labor case that sought to apply the legal concept of conspiracy to union picketing and organization efforts. The case grew out of a coal miners' strike in [[Clearfield County, Pennsylvania]] which was supported by the MNA, then numerically one of the largest American trade unions. First over fifty of the striking workers were tried upon a charge of criminal conspiracy and thirty-six of them were convicted with some sentenced to jail, although they appeared to have been guilty of no more than peaceful picketing. Then [[John Siney]], the president of the MNA, and Xingo Parks, one of the union\u2019s best organizers, were tried on the same charge. Siney was acquitted, but Parks convicted, although pardoned shortly thereafter<ref>Witte, Edwin E., Early American Labor Cases, 35 Yale Law Journal 7, 1926, pp. 830-31</ref>.\n\nFollowing the disputed presidential election of 1876, Carpenter was hired by supporters of the Democratic candidate [[Samuel J. Tilden]] to examine Louisiana's vote counts and argue for victory over Republican [[Rutherford B. Hayes]]. Carpenter's first-hand accounts of the corrupt Republican state administration gave the Democrats some reason for hope, but ultimately the partisan make-up of the special electoral commission (7 Republicans, 6 Democrats) and its refusal to look behind the certified counts made many of their rulings a forgone conclusive win for Hayes.<ref>Thompson, pp. 247-253</ref>\n\n==Return to the senate==\nDespite ongoing press criticism and declining health, in 1878 Carpenter launched a bid for the senate seat occupied by Republican [[Timothy Howe]]. With the help of a strong lobby, he won over enough votes in the legislature to prevail over state party boss (and former friend) Elisha W. Keyes.<ref>Thompson, pp. 254-264</ref>\n\nCarpenter's second term as senator lacked the political drama of his Reconstruction years. He spoke in favor of President [[Rutherford B. Hayes]]'s maintenance of federal troops at southern polling places. He also vigorously opposed the Democrats' proposed pardoning of General [[Fitz-John Porter]] for ignoring General [[John Pope (military officer)|John Pope]]'s orders at [[Manassas]] in 1863, arguing that the power of pardon resides solely with the president.<ref>Thompson, pp. 264-266</ref> Carpenter remained a loyal supporter of President Grant in his quest for a third term, igniting bitter debates between Carpenter and White House aspirant Senator [[James G. Blaine]] of Maine.<ref>Thompson, pp. 268-270.</ref>\n\n==Death==\nWhile Carpenter's evident declining health was attributed to his indulgent lifestyle, he also suffered from the lung congestion of [[Bright's disease]]. After a cycle of relapses and recoveries he died on February 24, 1881 at his Washington, D.C. home surrounded by friends and family. He was buried at Forest Home Cemetery in Milwaukee.<ref>Thompson, pp. 275-280.</ref>\n\n==Family==\nIn 1855 Carpenter married Caroline Dillingham, the daughter of Paul Dillingham.<ref>{{cite book |last=Huse |first=Hiram A. |title=A Memorial Sketch of Paul Dillingham: Officers and Members: Report of Proceedings of the Annual Meeting |volume=3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=99o8AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA77 |location=Montpelier, VT |publisher=Argus and Patriot Book and Job Printing |page=77|year=1892 }}</ref> They were the parents of four children.  Daughters Ada and Annie were born and died in 1860.<ref>Thompson, p.294</ref> The other two lived to adulthood\u2014a daughter named Lilian (1857\u20131942)<ref>Thompson{{page needed|date=February 2018}}</ref> and a son named Paul Dillingham Carpenter (1867\u20131932).<ref>Thompson{{page needed|date=February 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"yb\"/>  Paul D. Carpenter was an attorney in Milwaukee and also served as judge of the county court.<ref>{{cite book |last=Campbell |first=John A. |date=1902 |title=A Biographical History, with Portraits, of Prominent Men of the Great West |url=https://archive.org/details/biographicalhist00camp |location=Chicago, IL |publisher=Western Biographical and Engraving Co. |pages=[https://archive.org/details/biographicalhist00camp/page/221 221]\u2013222}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of United States Congress members who died in office (1790\u20131899)]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book |last=Thompson |first=E. Bruce |year=1954 |title=Matthew Hale Carpenter: Webster of the West |url=http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=uc1.b3288429;view=1up;seq=11 |location=Madison, Wis. |publisher=State Historical Society of Wisconsin}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [[Frank A. Flower|Flower, Frank A.]] ''[https://archive.org/details/lifematthewhale00flowgoog/page/n61 <!-- pg=1 --> Life of Matthew Hale Carpenter]''. Madison, Wis.: David Atwood & Co., 1883.\n* ''[https://archive.org/details/memorialaddress06addrgoog/page/n21 <!-- pg=1 --> Memorial Addresses on the Life and Character of Matthew H. Carpenter, A Senator from Wisconsin]''. Washington, DC: U.S. Government Printing Office, 1882.\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{CongBio|C000171}}\n*{{Findagrave|6854506}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-sen}}\n{{U.S. 