{"title_page": "Mass Appeal Records", "text_new": "{{Short description|American record label}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox record label\n| name        = Mass Appeal Records\n| image       = Mass Appeal logo.png\n| image_size  = 250px\n| founded     = 2014\n| founder     = [[Nas|Nasir \"Nas\" Jones]] <br> Peter Bittenbender\n| status      = Active\n| distributor = [[RED Distribution]]\n[[Universal Music Group|Universal]]<ref name=\"univ\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.universalmusic.com/mass-appeal-universal-music-group-announce-exclusive-global-distribution-agreement/ |title=MASS APPEAL AND UNIVERSAL MUSIC GROUP ANNOUNCE EXCLUSIVE GLOBAL DISTRIBUTION AGREEMENT |publisher=universalmusic.com|date =June 13, 2018 |accessdate=June 17, 2018 }}</ref>\n |genre       = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| country     = [[United States]]\n| location    = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| website      = {{URL|http://massappealrecords.com|Official website}}\n}}\n\n'''Mass Appeal Records''' is an American [[independent record label]] founded in 2014. The label is the music division of the [[Mass Appeal (magazine)|Mass Appeal Media Group]]. In May 2014, it was announced that American rapper [[Nas]] was launching an indie label with Mass Appeal with Peter Bittenbender of company [[Decon]]. The label's current roster includes artists such as: [[Nas]], [[DJ Shadow]], [[Mannie Fresh]], [[Dave East]], [[Fashawn]], [[Black Milk]], and [[Keyon Harrold]].\n\nSince its inception, the label has put out releases including the singles \"Old English\u201d from [[Young Thug]], [[Freddie Gibbs]], and [[ASAP Ferg]] and [[Jay Electronica]]\u2019s \u201c[[Exhibit C]]\u201d; albums such as [[Fashawn]]\u2019s ''[[The Ecology]]'', [[Pimp C]]'s ''[[Long Live the Pimp]]'', and [[J Dilla]]'s ''[[The Diary (J Dilla album)|The Diary]]'', and mixtapes such as [[Dave East]]'s ''[[Hate Me Now (mixtape)|Hate Me Now]]''.\n\n==History==\nOn October 24, 2014, the label released [[Run the Jewels]] album ''[[Run the Jewels 2]]''. The album was crowned as number-one album of the year by ''[[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]]'', ''[[Stereogum]]'' and ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''and number-two hip hop album of the year by ''[[Rolling Stone]]''. In 2015, [[Marvel Comics]] released comic book covers inspired by Run the Jewels.<ref>[https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/see-two-new-marvel-comics-covers-paying-tribute-to-run-the-jewels-20150116 New Marvel Comics Covers Paying Tribute to Run the Jewels] Retrieved on July 15, 2016.</ref>\n\nFollowing his signing to Mass Appeal, Fashawn released his long-awaited second album ''[[The Ecology]]'' on February 24, 2015. The album features guest appearances by [[Nas]], [[Aloe Blacc]], [[Dom Kennedy]], and more.<ref name=\"ecology\">{{cite web|url=http://massappeal.com/fashawn-the-ecology-tracklisting-tour-dates|title=Fashawn \"The Ecology\" Track Listing|date=January 27, 2015|publisher=massappeal.com|accessdate=February 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nMass Appeal Records released ''[[The Mountain Will Fall]]'', the fifth studio album by [[DJ Shadow]] on June 24, 2016. It was his first studio album since 2011's ''[[The Less You Know, the Better]]''. The album was ranked at number one on Top Dance/Electronic Albums at ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''.<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7430948/dj-shadow-first-no-1-top-dance-electronic-albums DJ Shadow Scores First No. 1 on Top Dance/Electronic Albums] Retrieved on July 15, 2016.</ref>\n\nOn December 4, 2015, the label released Pimp C's fifth album, the posthumous ''[[Long Live the Pimp]]''.<ref>[http://au.complex.com/music/2016/04/pimp-c-long-live-the-pimp-documentary Long Live the Pimp,' a Documentary on the Life and Legacy of Pimp C] Retrieved on July 15, 2016.</ref> The following year, on April 15, 2016, the label released [[J Dilla]]'s vocal album ''[[The Diary (J Dilla album)|The Diary]]''.<ref>[http://www.musictimes.com/articles/65721/20160219/nas-release-j-dilla-album-diary-2002-mass-appeal-records.htm Nas to Release J Dilla Album 'The Diary' from 2002 on Mass Appeal Records] Retrieved on July 15, 2016.</ref> The album was ranked at number two on ''Pitchfork''{{'}}s list of \"Most Promising\" releases of [[Record_Store_Day#2016|Record Store Day 2016]].<ref>[https://pitchfork.com/thepitch/1048-record-store-day-2016s-best-and-weirdest-bets Record Store Day 2016's Best and Weirdest Bets] Retrieved on July 15, 2016.</ref> [[NPR]] included \"[[Fuck the Police (J Dilla song)|Fuck the Police]]\" in their ''Songs We Love'' segment.<ref>[http://www.newsjs.com/url.php?p=http://www.npr.org/2016/04/07/473227000/songs-we-love-j-dilla-f-the-police Songs We Love: J Dilla, 'F*** The Police'] Retrieved on July 15, 2016.</ref> Mass Appeal released ''Rubble Kings: The Album'' on January 15, 2016.\n\nJ Dilla released ''[[The Diary (J Dilla album)|The Diary]]'' through Mass Appeal on April 15, 2016. DJ Shadow released ''[[The Mountain Will Fall]]'' on June 24, 2016. Mass Appeal released ''The Land (Music from the Motion Picture)'' on July 29, 2016. Dave East released ''[[Kairi Chanel]]'' on September 30, 2016. Boldy James released ''The Art of Rock Climbing'' on January 27, 2017, and ''House of Blues'' on February 24, 2017. Fashawn released ''Manna'' on August 11, 2017. Dave East released ''[[Paranoia: A True Story]]'' on August 18, 2017. Ezri released ''be right back'' on October 5, 2017. Dave East released ''[[Paranoia 2]]'' on January 16, 2018. Black Milk released ''[[Fever (Black Milk album)|Fever]]'' on February 23, 2018. In May 2017, Mass Appeal announced a joint venture publishing company with Pulse Music Group.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/music/news/pulse-music-group-mass-appeal-partner-joint-venture-1202444721/|title=Pulse Music Group, Mass Appeal Partner for Urban Culture-Themed Original Content|last=Staff|first=Variety|date=May 25, 2017|work=Variety|access-date=August 17, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> In June 2018, a new partnership with Universal Music Group<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.universalmusic.com/mass-appeal-universal-music-group-announce-exclusive-global-distribution-agreement/|title=Mass Appeal and Universal Music Group Announce Exclusive Global Distribution Agreement - UMG|date=June 13, 2018|work=UMG|access-date=August 17, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> was announced with the companies entering into a multi-year global agreement.\n\nOn June 15, 2018, Nas released his twelfth studio album ''[[Nasir (album)|Nasir]]'', through Mass Appeal Records and [[Def Jam Recordings]]. It succeeds Nas' album ''[[Life Is Good (Nas album)|Life Is Good]]'', released six years prior in 2012. The album was a part of the [[GOOD Music]] 7-song, 5-album rollout executive produced by Kanye West, featuring appearances from Kanye West, Puff Daddy, 070 Shake, Tony Williams, and The-Dream. ''Nasir'' debuted at number five on the US Billboard 200 with 77,000 album-equivalent units, of which 49,000 were pure album sales. It serves as Nas's twelfth top-ten album in the United States. \n\nIn August 2018, Cantrell released his debut EP ''Stardust 2 Angels''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8472035/cantrell-interview-mass-appeal-stardust-2-angels-ep|title=Mass Appeal Signee Cantrell Talks 'Stardust 2 Angels' EP, Love For Jam Skating & Why He's Hip-Hop's Deion Sanders|last=Elibert|first=Mark|date=August 24, 2018|website=Billboard|access-date=August 24, 2018}}</ref>  The project was accompanied by a Mass Appeal-produced documentary available via YouTube, entitled, \"Stardust 2: Cantrell on Skating, New Album and Albany, GA | Mass Appeal\".<ref>{{Citation|last=Mass Appeal|title=Stardust 2: Cantrell on Skating, New Album and Albany, GA {{!}} Mass Appeal|date=2018-09-24|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VV9GkGbys_8|access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref> \n\nMass Appeal artist Stro released his debut project, ''Nice 2 Meet You, Again''<ref name=\":0\" /> on October 19, 2018. The EP has one feature by Mannywellz. Cuz Lightyear released ''Blue Slime''<ref name=\":1\" /> on November 30, 2018, featuring rappers [[Lil Baby]], [[Killer Mike]], and [[Yung Bans]]. Mass Appeal's resident punk band, The 1865, released ''Don't Tread On We!'' on January 25, 2019. The 1865 has four members: Mass Appeal's own director, [[Sacha Jenkins]], alongside Carolyn \"Honeychild\" Coleman, Flora Lucini, Chuck Treece, and Jason \"Biz\" Lucas. The label then released a compilation album called the ''Starting 5: Vol. 1'' on February 5, 2019, with features from Nas, Black Milk, and Liana Bank$. The project had an accompanying tour during rollout, The Starting 5 Tour, with artists Ezri, Stro, Fashawn, Cantrell, and 070 Phi.\n\n==Artists==\n===Current===\n* [[Nas]]\n* [[Divine (rapper)|Divine]]\n* [[Run the Jewels]]\n* [[Fashawn]]\n* [[Boldy James]]\n* [[Dave East]]\n* [[De La Soul]]\n* [[Mannie Fresh]]\n* [[DJ Shadow]]\n* [[Black Milk]]\n* [[Kiing Shooter]]\n* [[Cantrell (rapper)|Cantrell]]\n* [[N.O.R.E.]]\n* [[Astro (rapper)|Stro]]\n*[[SL Jones|Cuz Lightyear]]\n* 070 Phi<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://hiphopdx.com/news/id.49703/title.dxclusive-070-phi-signs-to-mass-appeal-records|title=#DXCLUSIVE: 070 Phi Signs To Mass Appeal Records|work=[[HipHopDX]]|access-date=2019-01-01|language=en}}</ref>\n* atm<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://hiphopdx.com/news/id.51049/title.jersey-rapper-atm-signs-to-mass-appeal-records-announces-self-titled-ep|title=Jersey Rapper atm Signs To Mass Appeal Records & Announces Self-Titled EP|work=HipHopDX|access-date=August 30, 2019|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Former===\n* [[Pimp C]] <small>(Deceased)</small>\n\n==Discography==\n* [[Run the Jewels]] - ''[[Run the Jewels 2]]'' - October 24, 2014\n* [[Fashawn]] - ''[[The Ecology]]'' - February 24, 2015\n* [[Boldy James]] - ''Trapper's Alley 2'' - February 27, 2015\n* [[The Alchemist (musician)|The Alchemist]] and [[Oh No (musician)|Oh No]] - ''[[Welcome to Los Santos]]'' - April 21, 2015\n* [[Gangrene (group)|Gangrene]] - ''[[You Disgust Me]]'' - August 7, 2015\n* Run the Jewels - ''[[Meow the Jewels]]'' - September 25, 2015\n* [[Dave East]] - ''Hate Me Now'' - October 1, 2015\n* [[Pimp C]] - ''[[Long Live the Pimp]]'' - December 4, 2015\n* Various Artists - ''Rubble Kings: The Album'' - January 15, 2016\n* [[J Dilla]] - ''[[The Diary (J Dilla album)|The Diary]]'' - April 15, 2016\n* [[DJ Shadow]] - ''[[The Mountain Will Fall]]'' - June 24, 2016\n* Various Artists - ''The Land (Music from the Motion Picture)'' - July 29, 2016\n* Dave East - ''[[Kairi Chanel]]'' - September 30, 2016\n* Boldy James - ''The Art of Rock Climbing'' - January 27, 2017\n* Boldy James - ''House of Blues'' - February 24, 2017\n* Fashawn - ''Manna'' - August 11, 2017\n* Dave East - ''[[Paranoia: A True Story]]'' - August 18, 2017\n*Ezri - ''be right back'' - October 5, 2017\n* Dave East - ''[[Paranoia 2]]'' - January 16, 2018\n* Black Milk - ''Fever'' - February 23, 2018\n* Nas - ''[[Nasir (album)|Nasir]]'' - June 15, 2018\n*Cantrell - ''Stardust 2 Angels'' - August 24, 2018\n*Stro - ''Nice 2 Meet You, Again''<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/stro-drops-off-his-new-ep-nice-2-meet-you-again-new-mixtape.118526.html|title=Stro Drops Off His New EP \"Nice 2 Meet You, Again\"|work=HotNewHipHop|access-date=2018-11-30}}</ref> - October 19, 2018\n*Cuz Lightyear - ''Blue Slime''<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://hiphop...s-killer-mike|title=Cuz Lightyear Drops \"Blue Slime\" Album Featuring Lil Baby, Yung Bans & Killer Mike|last=Clark|first=Trent|date=November 30, 2018|website=Hip Hop DX|access-date=November 30, 2018}}</ref> - November 30, 2018\n*The 1865 - ''Don't Tread On We!'' - January 25, 2019\n*Mass Appeal - ''[https://hiphopdx.com/news/id.50178/title.mass-appeal-drops-starting-5-vol-1-lp-featuring-nas-black-milk-fashawn-stro-more Starting 5: Vol. 1]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hiphopdx.com/news/id.50178/title.mass-appeal-drops-starting-5-vol-1-lp-featuring-nas-black-milk-fashawn-stro-more|title=Mass Appeal Drops \"Starting 5: Vol. 1\" LP Featuring Nas, Black Milk, Fashawn, Stro & More|last=http://hiphopdx.com|first=HipHopDX-|date=2019-02-04|website=HipHopDX|access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref>- February 5, 2019\n*Cantrell - ''[https://hiphopdx.com/reviews/id.3384/title.review-mass-appeals-cantrell-gets-heartfelt-on-devil-never-even-lived DEVIL NEVER EVEN LIVED]'' - March 22, 2019\n*atm - ''atm'' - April 26, 2019\n* Nas - ''[[The Lost Tapes 2]]'' - July 19, 2019\n* Dave East - ''[[Survival (Dave East album)|Survival]] - November 8, 2019\n\n==See also==\n*[[Mass Appeal (magazine)|Mass Appeal Magazine]]\n*[[Ill Will Records]]\n*[[Decon Records]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.runthejewels.net/ Official website-Run the Jewels]\n* [http://djshadow.com/ Official website- DJ Shadow]\n\n{{Nas}}\n{{Dave East|state=autocollapse}} \n{{El-P}}\n{{Killer Mike}}\n{{The Alchemist}}\n\n[[Category:American record labels]]\n[[Category:Nas]]\n[[Category:Hip hop record labels]]\n[[Category:Record labels established in 2014]]\n[[Category:Vanity record labels]]\n[[Category:Hardcore hip hop record labels]]\n[[Category:2014 establishments in New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|American record label}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2018}}\n{{Infobox record label\n| name        = Mass Appeal Records\n| image       = Mass Appeal logo.png\n| image_size  = 250px\n| founded     = 2014\n| founder     = [[Nas|Nasir \"Nas\" Jones]] <br> Peter Bittenbender\n| status      = Active\n| distributor = [[RED Distribution]]\n[[Universal Music Group|Universal]]<ref name=\"univ\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.universalmusic.com/mass-appeal-universal-music-group-announce-exclusive-global-distribution-agreement/ |title=MASS APPEAL AND UNIVERSAL MUSIC GROUP ANNOUNCE EXCLUSIVE GLOBAL DISTRIBUTION AGREEMENT |publisher=universalmusic.com|date =June 13, 2018 |accessdate=June 17, 2018 }}</ref>\n |genre       = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| country     = [[United States]]\n| location    = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| website      = {{URL|http://massappealrecords.com|Official website}}\n}}\n\n'''Mass Appeal Records''' is an American [[independent record label]] founded in 2014. The label is the music division of the [[Mass Appeal (magazine)|Mass Appeal Media Group]]. In May 2014, it was announced that American rapper [[Nas]] was launching an indie label with Mass Appeal with Peter Bittenbender of company [[Decon]]. The label's current roster includes artists such as: [[Nas]], [[DJ Shadow]], [[Mannie Fresh]], [[Dave East]], [[Fashawn]], [[Black Milk]], and [[Keyon Harrold]].\n\nSince its inception, the label has put out releases including the singles \"Old English\u201d from [[Young Thug]], [[Freddie Gibbs]], and [[ASAP Ferg]] and [[Jay Electronica]]\u2019s \u201c[[Exhibit C]]\u201d; albums such as [[Fashawn]]\u2019s ''[[The Ecology]]'', [[Pimp C]]'s ''[[Long Live the Pimp]]'', and [[J Dilla]]'s ''[[The Diary (J Dilla album)|The Diary]]'', and mixtapes such as [[Dave East]]'s ''[[Hate Me Now (mixtape)|Hate Me Now]]''.\n\n==History==\nOn October 24, 2014, the label released [[Run the Jewels]] album ''[[Run the Jewels 2]]''. The album was crowned as number-one album of the year by ''[[Pitchfork Media|Pitchfork]]'', ''[[Stereogum]]'' and ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''and number-two hip hop album of the year by ''[[Rolling Stone]]''. In 2015, [[Marvel Comics]] released comic book covers inspired by Run the Jewels.<ref>[https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/see-two-new-marvel-comics-covers-paying-tribute-to-run-the-jewels-20150116 New Marvel Comics Covers Paying Tribute to Run the Jewels] Retrieved on July 15, 2016.</ref>\n\nFollowing his signing to Mass Appeal, Fashawn released his long-awaited second album ''[[The Ecology]]'' on February 24, 2015. The album features guest appearances by [[Nas]], [[Aloe Blacc]], [[Dom Kennedy]], and more.<ref name=\"ecology\">{{cite web|url=http://massappeal.com/fashawn-the-ecology-tracklisting-tour-dates|title=Fashawn \"The Ecology\" Track Listing|date=January 27, 2015|publisher=massappeal.com|accessdate=February 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nMass Appeal Records released ''[[The Mountain Will Fall]]'', the fifth studio album by [[DJ Shadow]] on June 24, 2016. It was his first studio album since 2011's ''[[The Less You Know, the Better]]''. The album was ranked at number one on Top Dance/Electronic Albums at ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''.<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/7430948/dj-shadow-first-no-1-top-dance-electronic-albums DJ Shadow Scores First No. 1 on Top Dance/Electronic Albums] Retrieved on July 15, 2016.</ref>\n\nOn December 4, 2015, the label released Pimp C's fifth album, the posthumous ''[[Long Live the Pimp]]''.<ref>[http://au.complex.com/music/2016/04/pimp-c-long-live-the-pimp-documentary Long Live the Pimp,' a Documentary on the Life and Legacy of Pimp C] Retrieved on July 15, 2016.</ref> The following year, on April 15, 2016, the label released [[J Dilla]]'s vocal album ''[[The Diary (J Dilla album)|The Diary]]''.<ref>[http://www.musictimes.com/articles/65721/20160219/nas-release-j-dilla-album-diary-2002-mass-appeal-records.htm Nas to Release J Dilla Album 'The Diary' from 2002 on Mass Appeal Records] Retrieved on July 15, 2016.</ref> The album was ranked at number two on ''Pitchfork''{{'}}s list of \"Most Promising\" releases of [[Record_Store_Day#2016|Record Store Day 2016]].<ref>[https://pitchfork.com/thepitch/1048-record-store-day-2016s-best-and-weirdest-bets Record Store Day 2016's Best and Weirdest Bets] Retrieved on July 15, 2016.</ref> [[NPR]] included \"[[Fuck the Police (J Dilla song)|Fuck the Police]]\" in their ''Songs We Love'' segment.<ref>[http://www.newsjs.com/url.php?p=http://www.npr.org/2016/04/07/473227000/songs-we-love-j-dilla-f-the-police Songs We Love: J Dilla, 'F*** The Police'] Retrieved on July 15, 2016.</ref> Mass Appeal released ''Rubble Kings: The Album'' on January 15, 2016.\n\nJ Dilla released ''[[The Diary (J Dilla album)|The Diary]]'' through Mass Appeal on April 15, 2016. DJ Shadow released ''[[The Mountain Will Fall]]'' on June 24, 2016. Mass Appeal released ''The Land (Music from the Motion Picture)'' on July 29, 2016. Dave East released ''[[Kairi Chanel]]'' on September 30, 2016. Boldy James released ''The Art of Rock Climbing'' on January 27, 2017, and ''House of Blues'' on February 24, 2017. Fashawn released ''Manna'' on August 11, 2017. Dave East released ''[[Paranoia: A True Story]]'' on August 18, 2017. Ezri released ''be right back'' on October 5, 2017. Dave East released ''[[Paranoia 2]]'' on January 16, 2018. Black Milk released ''[[Fever (Black Milk album)|Fever]]'' on February 23, 2018. In May 2017, Mass Appeal announced a joint venture publishing company with Pulse Music Group<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2017/music/news/pulse-music-group-mass-appeal-partner-joint-venture-1202444721/|title=Pulse Music Group, Mass Appeal Partner for Urban Culture-Themed Original Content|last=Staff|first=Variety|date=May 25, 2017|work=Variety|access-date=August 17, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>. In June 2018, a new partnership with Universal Music Group<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.universalmusic.com/mass-appeal-universal-music-group-announce-exclusive-global-distribution-agreement/|title=Mass Appeal and Universal Music Group Announce Exclusive Global Distribution Agreement - UMG|date=June 13, 2018|work=UMG|access-date=August 17, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> was announced with the companies entering into a multi-year global agreement.\n\nOn June 15, 2018, Nas released his twelfth studio album ''[[Nasir (album)|Nasir]]'', through Mass Appeal Records and [[Def Jam Recordings]]. It succeeds Nas' album ''[[Life Is Good (Nas album)|Life Is Good]]'', released six years prior in 2012. The album was a part of the [[GOOD Music]] 7-song, 5-album rollout executive produced by Kanye West, featuring appearances from Kanye West, Puff Daddy, 070 Shake, Tony Williams, and The-Dream. ''Nasir'' debuted at number five on the US Billboard 200 with 77,000 album-equivalent units, of which 49,000 were pure album sales. It serves as Nas's twelfth top-ten album in the United States. \n\nIn August 2018, Cantrell released his debut EP ''Stardust 2 Angels''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8472035/cantrell-interview-mass-appeal-stardust-2-angels-ep|title=Mass Appeal Signee Cantrell Talks 'Stardust 2 Angels' EP, Love For Jam Skating & Why He's Hip-Hop's Deion Sanders|last=Elibert|first=Mark|date=August 24, 2018|website=Billboard|access-date=August 24, 2018}}</ref>  The project was accompanied by a Mass Appeal-produced documentary available via YouTube, entitled, \"Stardust 2: Cantrell on Skating, New Album and Albany, GA | Mass Appeal\"<ref>{{Citation|last=Mass Appeal|title=Stardust 2: Cantrell on Skating, New Album and Albany, GA {{!}} Mass Appeal|date=2018-09-24|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VV9GkGbys_8|access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref>. \n\nMass Appeal artist Stro released his debut project, ''Nice 2 Meet You, Again''<ref name=\":0\" /> on October 19, 2018. The EP has one feature by Mannywellz. Cuz Lightyear released ''Blue Slime''<ref name=\":1\" /> on November 30, 2018, featuring rappers [[Lil Baby]], [[Killer Mike]], and [[Yung Bans]]. Mass Appeal's resident punk band, The 1865, released ''Don't Tread On We!'' on January 25, 2019. The 1865 has four members: Mass Appeal's own director, [[Sacha Jenkins]], alongside Carolyn \"Honeychild\" Coleman, Flora Lucini, Chuck Treece, and Jason \"Biz\" Lucas. The label then released a compilation album called the ''Starting 5: Vol. 1'' on February 5, 2019, with features from Nas, Black Milk, and Liana Bank$. The project had an accompanying tour during rollout, The Starting 5 Tour, with artists Ezri, Stro, Fashawn, Cantrell, and 070 Phi.\n\n==Artists==\n===Current===