t - ''[[Paranoia: A True Story]]'' - August 18, 2017\n*Ezri - ''be right back'' - October 5, 2017\n* Dave East - ''[[Paranoia 2]]'' - January 16, 2018\n* Black Milk - ''Fever'' - February 23, 2018\n* Nas - ''[[Nasir (album)|Nasir]]'' - June 15, 2018\n*Cantrell - ''Stardust 2 Angels'' - August 24, 2018\n*Stro - ''Nice 2 Meet You, Again''<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.hotnewhiphop.com/stro-drops-off-his-new-ep-nice-2-meet-you-again-new-mixtape.118526.html|title=Stro Drops Off His New EP \"Nice 2 Meet You, Again\"|work=HotNewHipHop|access-date=2018-11-30}}</ref> - October 19, 2018\n*Cuz Lightyear - ''Blue Slime''<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://hiphop...s-killer-mike|title=Cuz Lightyear Drops \"Blue Slime\" Album Featuring Lil Baby, Yung Bans & Killer Mike|last=Clark|first=Trent|date=November 30, 2018|website=Hip Hop DX|access-date=November 30, 2018}}</ref> - November 30, 2018\n*The 1865 - ''Don't Tread On We!'' - January 25, 2019\n*Mass Appeal - ''[https://hiphopdx.com/news/id.50178/title.mass-appeal-drops-starting-5-vol-1-lp-featuring-nas-black-milk-fashawn-stro-more Starting 5: Vol. 1]''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hiphopdx.com/news/id.50178/title.mass-appeal-drops-starting-5-vol-1-lp-featuring-nas-black-milk-fashawn-stro-more|title=Mass Appeal Drops \"Starting 5: Vol. 1\" LP Featuring Nas, Black Milk, Fashawn, Stro & More|last=http://hiphopdx.com|first=HipHopDX-|date=2019-02-04|website=HipHopDX|access-date=2019-04-08}}</ref>- February 5, 2019\n*Cantrell - ''[https://hiphopdx.com/reviews/id.3384/title.review-mass-appeals-cantrell-gets-heartfelt-on-devil-never-even-lived DEVIL NEVER EVEN LIVED]'' - March 22, 2019\n*atm - ''atm'' - April 26, 2019\n* Nas - ''[[The Lost Tapes 2]]'' - July 19, 2019\n* Dave East - ''[[Survival (Dave East album)|Survival]] - November 8, 2019\n\n==See also==\n*[[Mass Appeal (magazine)|Mass Appeal Magazine]]\n*[[Ill Will Records]]\n*[[Decon Records]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.runthejewels.net/ Official website-Run the Jewels]\n* [http://djshadow.com/ Official website- DJ Shadow]\n\n{{Nas}}\n{{Dave East|state=autocollapse}} \n{{El-P}}\n{{Killer Mike}}\n{{The Alchemist}}\n\n[[Category:American record labels]]\n[[Category:Nas]]\n[[Category:Hip hop record labels]]\n[[Category:Record labels established in 2014]]\n[[Category:Vanity record labels]]\n[[Category:Hardcore hip hop record labels]]\n[[Category:2014 establishments in New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "DannyS712", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing the location of periods / full stops", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mass_Appeal_Records"}
{"title_page": "Mission San Luis Obispo de Tolosa", "text_new": "{{Infobox Missions|\n  image=San Luis Obispo\n  De Tolosa had huge shooting in 1834.|\n  name=Mission San Luis Obispo de Tolosa|\n  location=728 Monterey St.<br />[[San Luis Obispo, California]] 93401|\n  originalname=''La Misi\u00f3n de San Lu\u00eds Obispo de Tolosa''&nbsp;<ref>Leffingwell, p. 85</ref>|\n  translation=The Mission of Saint Louis Bishop of Toulouse|\n  namesake=[[Louis of Toulouse|Saint Louis of Anjou]], Bishop of [[Toulouse]], France|\n  nickname=\"Prince of the Missions\"&nbsp;<ref>Schulte-Peevers, p. 682</ref><br>\"Mission in the Valley of Bears\"&nbsp;<ref name = \"yenne56\"/><br>\"The Accidental Mission\"&nbsp;<ref name=\"ruscin53\">Ruscin, p. 53</ref>|\n  founded=September 1, 1772&nbsp;<ref name=\"yenne56\">Yenne, p. 56</ref>|\n  foundedby=Father Presidente [[Jun\u00edpero Serra]]&nbsp;<ref>Ruscin, p. 196</ref>||\n  foundingorder=Fifth|\n  militarydistrict=Third <ref>'''Forbes,''' p. 202</ref>|\n  nativetribe=[[Chumash (tribe)|Chumash]]<br>Obispe\u00f1o\n| placename=''Tilhini''&nbsp;<ref>Ruscin, p. 195</ref>|\n  baptisms=2,644 <ref name = \"krell315\"/>|\n  marriages=763 <ref name = \"krell315\"/>|\n  burials=2,268 <ref name=\"krell315\">Krell, p. 315: as of December 31, 1832; information adapted from Engelhardt's ''Missions and Missionaries of California''.</ref>|\n  owner=[[Roman Catholic Diocese of Monterey]]|\n  currentuse=Parish Church / Museum\n| coordinates = {{coord|35|16|50|N|120|39|52|W|type:landmark_region:UA-CA|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin=California\n|  designation1=California\n|  designation1_number=325<ref>{{cite ohp | title=Mission San Luis Obispo de Tolosa | id=325}}</ref>\n|  website=http://www.missionsanluisobispo.org\n}} \n\n'''Mission San Luis Obispo de Tolosa''' ({{lang-es|Misi\u00f3n San Lu\u00eds Obispo de Tolosa}}) is a [[Spanish missions in California|Spanish mission]] founded in 1772 by Father [[Jun\u00edpero Serra]] in [[San Luis Obispo, California]]. Named after [[Saint Louis of Toulouse|Saint Louis of Anjou]], the [[bishop of Toulouse]], the mission is the namesake of San Luis Obispo. Today, it offers tours of the beautiful church, gardens, school and small museum that holds a collection of its artifacts. Unlike other California missions, the San Luis Obispo Mission is open to the public every day of the year and is still a very popular parish for the town's Catholic community. \n\nThe Mission of San Luis Obispo is unusual in its design, in that its combination of [[Bell tower|belfry]] and [[Vestibule (Architecture)|vestibule]] are found nowhere else among the California missions. Like other churches, the main [[nave]] is short and narrow, but at the San Luis Obispo Mission, there is a secondary nave of almost equal size situated to the right of the [[altar]], making it the only L-shaped mission church in California.\n\n==History==\nIn 1769, Gaspar de Portola traveled through California on his way to the Bay of Monterey and discovered the San Luis Obispo area.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://missionsanluisobispo.org/visit/#history|title=Visit|work=Mission San Luis Obispo de Toulosa|access-date=2018-10-23|language=en-US}}</ref> Expedition diarist and [[Franciscan]] missionary [[Juan Cresp\u00ed]] wrote that the soldiers called the place \"llano de los osos,\" or the \"level of the bears.\" Since then, mistranslations of the Crespi's diary have called this area \"la canada de los osos\" (the canyon of the bears) which has been further mistranslated as the \"valley of the bears.\" Portola followed the same route the following year, on his way to establish the [[Presidio of Monterey]]. Missionary president [[Jun\u00edpero Serra]], traveling by sea, met the Portola party there and founded San Carlos Borremeo, in Monterey, which was moved to Carmel the following year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://missionsanluisobispo.org/visit/#history|title=Visit|work=Mission San Luis Obispo de Toulosa|access-date=2018-10-23|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nWhen food supplies started to dwindle at the mission, Serra remembered the stories of the \"valley of the bears.\" He decided to send a hunting expedition to San Luis Obispo to help feed the [[Spanish people|Spanish]] and neophytes (natives that converted to Christianity) in Monterey. The huge success of the hunting expedition caused Jun\u00edpero Serra to consider building a mission in that area. Upon further investigation, he was convinced that [[San Luis Obispo]] would be a perfect site for a mission, based on its surplus of natural resources, good weather and the [[Chumash (tribe)|Chumash]], a local, friendly Native American tribe who could help provide labor. The mission became the fifth in the mission chain founded by Father Jun\u00edpero Serra.<ref name=history>{{cite web|url=http://www.missionsanluisobispo.org/history.html|title=Mission History| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110725004254/http://www.missionsanluisobispo.org/history.html |archive-date=25 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nFather Serra sent an expedition down south to [[San Luis Obispo]] to start building the mission, and on September 1, 1772, a cross was erected near [[San Luis Obispo Creek]] and Serra celebrated the first mass. However, following the first mass, Father Jun\u00edpero Serra left the responsibility of construction to Father Jose Cavaller. Father Cavaller, five soldiers and two neophytes began building what is now Mission San Luis Obispo de Tolosa.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://missionsanluisobispo.org/visit/#history|title=Visit|work=Mission San Luis Obispo de Toulosa|access-date=2018-10-23|language=en-US}}</ref> Father Cavaller received help in the building of the mission from the Chumash, who constructed [[palisade]]s, which would serve as temporary buildings for the mission. However, due to several Native American tribes which were determined to get rid of European settlers, they set these buildings ablaze. Because of this, Father Cavaller was forced to rebuild the buildings using adobe and tile structures.<ref name=morehistory>{{cite web|url=http://www.californiamissions.com/morehistory/sanluis.html|title=San Luis Obispo de Tolosa|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100128064536/http://www.californiamissions.com/morehistory/sanluis.html |archive-date=28 January 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[Image: San Luis Obispo de Tolosa circa 1900 Keystone-Mast.jpg|thumb|300px|Mission San Luis Obispo de Tolosa as it looked ''circa'' 1900. Note that the wooden belfry has been removed and the chapel fa\u00e7ade has been modified substantially in the recent photo below.]]\n\nBeginning in 1794 Mission San Luis Obispo went through extensive building operations.<ref name=\"morehistory\" /> Buildings to accommodate the nearby Native Americans and many improvements to the mission, including storerooms, residences for single women, soldiers barracks and mills were added.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://missionsanluisobispo.org/visit/#history|title=Visit|work=Mission San Luis Obispo de Toulosa|access-date=2018-10-23|language=en-US}}</ref> The renovation was finally finished after completion of the [[Quadrangle (architecture)|quadrangle]] in 1819, and celebrated a year later by the arrival of two mission bells from [[Lima, Peru]].<ref name=\"SanLuis\">{{cite web|url=http://www.californiamissions.com/cahistory/sanluis.html|title=Mission San Luis Obispo de Tolosa|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100121034159/http://www.californiamissions.com/cahistory/sanluis.html|archive-date=21 January 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref> The arrival of the bells marked the end of improvements made to Mission San Luis Obispo de Tolosa for many years.<ref name=\"history\" /> In 1830 Father Luis Gil y Taboada took over the mission, but he died three years later. Then in 1842, the death of Father Ramon Abella marked the last [[Franciscan]] at the mission.<ref name=\"history\" />\n\nIn 1845, Governor [[P\u00edo Pico]] declared the mission buildings for sale and he sold everything except the church for a total of $510. [[John C. Fr\u00e9mont]] and his \"California Battalion\" used the mission as a base of operations during their war with [[Mexico]] in 1846 (see [[Bear Flag Revolt]]). The mission fell to ruins during the period of [[Mexican secularization act of 1833|secularization]] and the priests who were left would rent out rooms to help support the mission. The Mission San Lu\u00eds Obispo de Tolosa became the first [[courthouse]] and [[County jail|jail]] in [[San Luis Obispo County, California]]. In 1850, when California became a part of the United States, the first California bishop, Joseph Alemany, petitioned the Government to return some of the mission lands back to the Church.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://missionsanluisobispo.org/visit/#history|title=Visit|work=Mission San Luis Obispo de Toulosa|access-date=2018-10-23|language=en-US}}</ref> Since then, it has undergone major civic, political and structural changes, but real restoration did not begin until 1933.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://missionsanluisobispo.org/visit/#history|title=Visit|work=Mission San Luis Obispo de Toulosa|access-date=2018-10-23|language=en-US}}</ref> The mission is still the center of the busy downtown area, and functions as a [[Roman Catholic]] [[parish]] church for the City of San Luis Obispo in the [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Monterey in California|Diocese of Monterey]]. In 1970 the Mission was recognized as the center of the City of [[San Luis Obispo]], with the dedication of Mission Plaza.<ref name=history/>\n\n==Spanish Origin==\nIn 1602, the Spanish began to show interest in California and sent [[Sebasti\u00e1n Vizca\u00edno]], a pearl fisher, to explore the area. Vizcaino traveled the coast naming many of the cities that are important to the California coast today such as [[San Diego]], Santa Barbara and Monterey. Spain finally chose to create Vizcaino's suggested chain of missions when it was proven that California was indeed part of the continent. The goal of creating the chain was given to the [[Franciscan Order]]. While Spain had economic motives for establishing a stronghold in California, the [[Franciscan]] order of the [[Roman Catholic Church|Catholic]] Church also had religious motives.<ref name=TheTropics>{{cite web| url=http://www.geocities.com/TheTropics/6788/missions.html| title= Mision San Carlos, Carmel| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091027111530/http://www.geocities.com/TheTropics/6788/missions.html | archive-date=27 October 2009| url-status=dead}}</ref>  With these factors in mind the missions were created in order to control the coast so that the ships from Spain would remain safe as well as bring the [[Natives]] to the Catholic faith. Re-education became the method for reaching Spain's religious and economic goals as they strived to convert the Native Americans to Catholicism as well as make them loyal Spanish subjects.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Spanish missions in California]]\n* [[USNS Mission San Luis Obispo|''Mission San Luis Obispo'']] \u2013 a [[USNS Mission Buenaventura|''Mission Buenaventura'']] Class [[Oiler (ship)|fleet oiler]] built during World War II.\n* [[City of San Luis Obispo Historic Resources]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n* {{cite book|author=Forbes, Alexander|year=1839|title=California: A History of Upper and Lower California|url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_NH4FAAAAQAAJ|publisher=Smith, Elder and Co., Cornhill, London}}\n* {{cite book|author=Jones, Terry L. and Kathryn A. Klar (eds.)|year=2007|title=California Prehistory: Colonization, Culture, and Complexity|publisher=Altimira Press, Landham, Maryland|isbn=0-7591-0872-2}}\n* {{cite book|author=Krell, Dorothy (ed.)|year=1979|title=The California Missions: A Pictorial History|publisher=Sunset Publishing Corporation, Menlo Park, California|isbn=0-376-05172-8}}\n* {{cite book|author=Leffingwell, Randy|year=2005|title=California Missions and Presidios: The History & Beauty of the Spanish Missions|publisher=Voyageur Press, Inc., Stillwater, Minnesota|isbn=0-89658-492-5}}\n* {{cite book|author=Paddison, Joshua (ed.)|year=1999|title=A World Transformed: Firsthand Accounts of California Before the Gold Rush|publisher=Heyday Books, Berkeley, California|isbn=1-890771-13-9|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/worldtransformed00josh}}\n* {{cite book|author=Ruscin, Terry|year=1999|title=Mission Memoirs|publisher=Sunbelt Publications, San Diego, California|isbn=0-932653-30-8}}\n* {{cite book|author=Schulte-Peevers, Andrea|year=1996|title=California|publisher=Lonely Planet Publications, Oakland, California|isbn=1-74059-951-9}}\n* {{cite book|author=Yenne, Bill|year=2004|title=The Missions of California|publisher=Advantage Publishers Group, San Diego, California|isbn=1-59223-319-8}}\n* [http://www.missiontour.org/sanluisobispo/index.htm Mission Tour]\n* [http://www.chumashindian.com/ Chumash Indians]\n* [http://www.santaynezchumash.org/history.html Chumash History]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070302045829/http://content.scholastic.com/browse/article.jsp?id=5032 Spanish Missions]\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Mission San Luis Obispo de Tolosa}}\n* [http://www.missionsanluisobispo.org/ Mission San Luis Obispo] - official site\n* [http://www.doublepup.com/images/luisobi.gif Elevation & Site Layout sketches of the Mission proper]\n* [http://www.calisphere.universityofcalifornia.edu/browse/keyword/%22Mission+San+Luis+Obispo%22 Early photographs, sketches, land surveys of Mission San Luis Obispo de Tolosa], via Calisphere, California Digital Library\n* {{cite web|last=Howser|first=Huell|title=California Missions (104)|url=http://blogs.chapman.edu/huell-howser-archives/2000/12/08/california-missions-california-missions-104/|work=California Missions|publisher=[[Chapman University]] Huell Howser Archive|authorlink=Huell Howser|date=December 8, 2000}}\n\n{{Roman Catholic Diocese of Monterey in California}}\n{{California Missions}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mission San Luis Obispo De Tolosa}}\n[[Category:Spanish missions in California|San Luis Obispo de Tolosa]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in San Luis Obispo, California]]\n[[Category:1772 in Alta California]]\n[[Category:Churches in San Luis Obispo County, California]]\n[[Category:Museums in San Luis Obispo County, California]]\n[[Category:1772 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Religious organizations established in 1772]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic churches completed in 1819]]\n[[Category:18th-century Roman Catholic church buildings]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic Diocese of Monterey in California]]\n[[Category:California Historical Landmarks]]\n[[Category:History of San Luis Obispo County, California]]\n[[Category:Religious museums in California]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Missions|\n  image=San Luis Obispo\n  De Tolosa had huge shooting in 1834.|\n  name=Mission San Luis Obispo de Tolosa|\n  location=728 Monterey St.<br />[[San Luis Obispo, California]] 93401|\n  originalname=''La Misi\u00f3n de San Lu\u00eds Obispo de Tolosa''&nbsp;<ref>Leffingwell, p. 85</ref>|\n  translation=The Mission of Saint Louis Bishop of Toulouse|\n  namesake=[[Louis of Toulouse|Saint Louis of Anjou]], Bishop of [[Toulouse]], France|\n  nickname=\"Prince of the Missions\"&nbsp;<ref>Schulte-Peevers, p. 682</ref><br>\"Mission in the Valley of Bears\"&nbsp;<ref name = \"yenne56\"/><br>\"The Accidental Mission\"&nbsp;<ref name=\"ruscin53\">Ruscin, p. 53</ref>|\n  founded=September 1, 1772&nbsp;<ref name=\"yenne56\">Yenne, p. 56</ref>|\n  foundedby=Father Presidente [[Jun\u00edpero Serra]]&nbsp;<ref>Ruscin, p. 196</ref>||\n  foundingorder=Fifth|\n  militarydistrict=Third <ref>'''Forbes,''' p. 202</ref>|\n  nativetribe=[[Chumash (tribe)|Chumash]]<br>Obispe\u00f1o\n| placename=''Tilhini''&nbsp;<ref>Ruscin, p. 195</ref>|\n  baptisms=2,644 <ref name = \"krell315\"/>|\n  marriages=763 <ref name = \"krell315\"/>|\n  burials=2,268 <ref name=\"krell315\